<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Singleton     06-26 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singleton,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Front Of Singleton's Home, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small bomb was hurled at the home listed as
the address of rapist-mutilator Lawrence Singleton on Saturday
night, but the explosion caused no injuries or property damage,
authorities said.
   The homemade bomb detonated in the front yard of the one-story
home just before 9 p.m., said Hillsborough County Sheriff's Lt. Ken
Allen.
   ``Lawrence Singleton was not in the house, his whereabouts are
still unknown at this time,'' Allen said.
   Singleton's brother, Walter, and sister-in-law, Diane, were the
only people in the home when the device exploded, leaving a heavy
white cloud, the officer said.
   While many in the quiet Forest Hills neighborhood heard the
explosion, there were no witnesses to who threw the device, Allen
said. Experts were examining bomb shards to determine what type of
device it was.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker,
chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead in a
ditch southeast of San Francisco in 1978.
   The gray-bearded 60-year-old former merchant seaman, who grew up
in Tampa, spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a California
prison. He completed a year-long probation and is now a free man.
   During his probation, Singleton was forced to flee six
California towns after residents objected to his presence. He ended
up finishing his probation in a trailer on the grounds of San
Quentin prison.
   Two weeks ago, he listed the address with authorities as
required of convicted felons under state law, but he has never been
seen there. His brother has said Singleton lives ``about two hours
away,'' but refuses to say exactly where.
   Angry area residents have held two meetings in the past month
asking deputies to locate Singleton so they can stop living in
fear. A local businessman and a radio station have each offered
Singleton $5,000 if he will pack up and go anywhere else.
</TEXT>
