<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Drugs     06-26 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baja Governor's Brothers Accused in Major Cocaine Smuggling Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers of the state governor of Baja
California Sur are under arrest on charges they took part in a
sophisticated drug ring that smuggled cocaine from Colombia to the
United States, authorities said.
   Authorities also said they arrested four others who participated
in the operation.
   The arrests were announced late Friday by the federal attorney
general's office.
   Authorities said rancher Agustin Liceaga Ruibal, 48, and
businessman Rene Liceaga Ruibal, 46, were part of a smuggling ring
that operated clandestine air strips, safe houses and
money-laundering businesses in several Mexican states.
   An emotional Gov. Victor Manuel Liceaga Ruibal called the case a
``family tragedy'' during a hastily called news conference in La
Paz, the state capital, late Friday. He said he knew nothing of his
brother's activities.
   ``I am completely clean,'' he declared.
   The governor said state authorities cooperated fully with the
federal investigation and would continue to do so.
   Authorities said his brothers allowed at least one of their
ranches to be used for clandestine air strips where drug-laden
planes en route from Colombia to the United States refueled.
Investigators said they have tracked at least 10 flights.
   In addition to the governor's brothers, four other people were
arrested: Jose Pineda Trinidad, Antonio Alcantara Varela, Ramon
Escamilla Vazquez and Maria Alicia Marquez Solis.
   Pineda Trinidad, who also used the name Jose Ponce de Leon, was
identified as head of the ring.
   Authorities said he laundered drug profits through his money
exchange house in Guadalajara and a real estate company. The
profits were allegedly stashed in U.S. and Mexican banks and in
Panama, where authorities said they found $10 million in a single
account.
   Panama has been recently reported to be a regional banking
center for drug smugglers. In February, a U.S. grand jury in
Florida indicted its military ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
on drug-trafficking charges.
   The attorney general's office said it has seized Pineada
Trinidad's property, which also included three homes and four
ranches in the central state of Jalisco.
   Authorities did not say when or where the arrests were made, but
said all six suspects were transferred to Mexico City to face a
variety of drug charges.
</TEXT>
