<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti     06-26 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Namphy Picks Duvalierist To Head Games Control Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The new military government has
chosen as president of the important Games Control Commission a
Jean-Claude Duvalier supporter who has kept a low profile since the
dictator fled two years ago.
   The appointment of Abel Jerome, a retired army colonel, was
announced over the state-run television station Friday night along
with that of other new civil servants.
   They were selected by the new military government of Lt. Gen.
Henry Namphy, who swept into power earlier this week after ousting
civilian President Leslie Manigat.
   The weekly lottery, which generates hundreds of thousands of
dollars, is a national passion. There are almost as many ticket
stalls in the capital as grocery stores.
   The Games Control Commission is the body established to ensure
the lottery is not rigged and that winners collect earnings.
   Under the Duvalier regime, the corrupt administrative body was a
lucrative source of income for the dictators and their allies.
   Jerome is widely reported to have participated in the 1964 mass
murders of a number of prominent families in Jeremie, a town in
southwestern Haiti. He has gained a reputation for exceptional
brutality after those and other killings.
   Jerome has maintained a low profile since the February l986
uprising that sent Duvalier into exile in France, ending 29 years
of dictatorship by his family.
</TEXT>
