<HEAD>U.N. Locked in Disarmament Squabble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-week-long U.N. session on
disarmament missed its deadline and dragged on into Sunday after
bitterly divided delegates failed to agree on a formula for world
peace.
   The session, which was scheduled to end Saturday night, was
extended after delegates could not reach a consensus on issues
ranging from missile defense systems known as ``Star Wars'' to
monitoring land-based weapons.
   After the progress of the U.S.-Soviet summits, the failure of
this first General Assembly session on disarmament in six years to
meet its timetable put on public display the deep divisions that
still exist between East and West.
   Delegates to the $7.4 million session, which has heard 135
speakers since it began May 31, could only agree to allow a
negotiating committee to continue work Saturday night. Informal
consultations were expected through the night before participants
reconvened, possibly early Sunday.
   Delegates have been locked in intense, sometimes acrimonious
debate in efforts to forge a final document settng forth an agenda
for peace.
   The United States and some of its Western allies were at odds
with most other nations on numerous issues, including priorities
for nuclear and conventional disarmament, Third World disarmament
and identifying Israel and South Africa as regional offenders.
   Delegates and U.N. officials said it was uncertain whether the
world body would be able to adopt a final document by consensus and
avoid a divisive vote.
</TEXT>
