misconduct allegations filed by the State Bar stemming from alleged
mishandling of clients' money.
   The State Bar's trial counsel office filed documents Friday
asking for a disciplinary hearing into allegations that Mitchelson
failed to return unearned fees of up to $25,000 promptly after
several clients fired him.
   ``We have in excess of 20 complaints against Mr. Mitchelson,''
State Bar chief trial counsel James A. Bascue said.
   Among those who filed complaints were actress Julie Newmar and
Eleanor Revson, sister-in-law of the founder of Revlon Cosmetics.
   Mitchelson, 60, who made headlines by winning palimony payments
for Michele Triola, the unwed, live-in girlfriend of actor Lee
Marvin in 1976, could face disciplinary actions ranging from a
simple warning to disbarment.
   Mitchelson said he was surprised by the allegations, which he
called ``a sudden attack.''
   ``I'm highly visible so I may be a prime target, but
nevertheless I will vigorously defend myself against these charges
as I have defended every case I've ever had,'' Mitchelson said by
phone from Tokyo.
   ``All these complaints are old complaints and at least two of
them have been previously rejected by the State Bar,'' he said.
   Ms. Newmar, who starred as ``Catwoman'' on the 1960s TV series
``Batman,'' Ms. Revson and others complained that Mitchelson took
retainers from them and delayed or refused to return unearned
portions of the fees after they fired him for alleged deception,
the Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions.
   The Bar also charged that Mitchelson failed to deposit clients'
funds in trust accounts, charged ``unconscionable'' fees, failed to
perform promised work, lied to a client and twice improperly asked
a client to withdraw her complaint to the State Bar over the return
of unearned fees.
