<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world-record holder in long-distance
tobacco spitting won his ninth accuracy title in the 34th annual
National Tobacco Spitting Contest, but was upset in the distance
contest by a novice.
   Restaurateur Jeff Barber, 27, of Ocean Springs hit three
bull's-eyes in three attempts to take the accuracy title Saturday,
proving he didn't bite off more than he could chew.
   But in the distance competition, Barber, nicknamed ``The
Faucet,'' spat 27 feet, 5 inches, far short of his 33 feet, 7{-inch
effort listed in the Guinness Book of World Records. Newcomer David
Singleton, 18, of Raleigh, took the 1988 distance title with a spit
of 28 feet, 10 inches.
   Eschewing health warnings about the dangers of chew, 11 men
turned out for the accuracy contest and an even dozen for the
distance. In the women's contest, two showed up at Billy John
Crumpton's farm 5 miles west of this Smith County town.
   Defending champion Peggy Woods, 31, of Brandon took her third
consecutive title with a spit of 15-2{ to win the women's title. An
accuracy contest was not held for the women.
   Woods said she could have spat farther, but the heat brought on
by the continuing drought had dried out her mouth.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You could say Kenny Jones and Lisa Rhodes
got married, but a better word for it might be hitched.
   The two truckers were married in traditional attire in a
traditional church Saturday, but the entourage that waited outside
consisted of 12 decorated tractor-trailers and 35 cars blaring
their horns in a connubial convoy.
   After the ceremony, Jones, an employee of Owen Mathias Trucking
of Assumption, jumped in his rig, ``Bar Hopper,'' with his bride,
and the convoy was off.
   The group, chatting via CB radio, trucked through downtown
Decatur, turning heads and drawing laughs from passers-by, as well
as honks from other motorists.
   ``This is all right,'' said the bride, a clerk for ADM Trucking
in Decatur who gets her trucking license in July. ``It's definitely
different.''
   ``It's just neat,'' Jones said of the turnout. ``I can't believe
it all happened. I didn't expect this many.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee's new automobile license
plates have given some county clerks a devil of a problem, but
others are managing to exorcise the trouble.
   Several clerks have been fielding complaints from motorists who
are unhappy that the number on their new three-letter, three digit
tags is 666 _ which some believe is the mark of the devil.
   ``Most of them won't take it when they get it,'' said Davidson
County Clerk Bill Covington. ``You might draw the wrong kind of
crowd.''
   Covington said his office has withdrawn the 666 plates from
Davidson county's stockpile _ all 366 of them.
   ``The thought never entered out minds,'' said Danny Shelton,
manager of Tennessee's license plate program of the 666
combination, which occurs every thousand plates. ``Registrants do
not have to accept the plates when they're issued.''
   Not all motorists have felt compelled to reject the number _
even one who's a man of the cloth.
   ``A lot of people mentioned it to me, especially since I'm a
minister,'' said John Miller of Nashville, pastor of the Tusculum
Church of Christ, who accepted a plate with 666. ``The beast is
very, very evil. But it has nothing to do with what number is on
your license plate or your Social Security card.''
