<HEAD>New Jet Crashes During Air Show; Two Dead, 60 Hurt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two dead, quote from passenger, other
details of crash; picks up 3rd graf pvs: An official...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MULHOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Airbus A320 jetliner carrying 127
people crashed during an air show in eastern France, killing at
least two people and injuring 60, district government officials
said.
   Witnesses said the Air France jet, which went into service a
month ago, clipped some trees at the edge of an airport runway and
crashed in a field nearby.
   An unidentified passenger, a 25-year-old woman, was quoted by
Agence France-Presse as saying that she heard she heard tree
branches rub against the plane's fuselage.
   ``Things started moving fast,'' she said. ``The plane hit the
ground hard and we had the feeling of a abrupt jolt. Then there was
a fire in the front of the aircraft.''
   She was quoted as saying that the plane's evacuation chutes were
deployed and many passengers aboard slid down and got off, running
a distance from the plane because they feared an explosion.
   The twin-engine jet was taking part in an air show in overcast,
humid weather.
   An official at the Ministry of Transport in Paris said the
accident occurred at 2:50 p.m. (8:50 a.m. EDT) while the plane was
on a low-altitude demonstration flight above the Mulhouse-Habsheim
airport. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Medical evacuation helicopters and ambulances rushed to the
airport, located about 18 miles north of the Swiss city of Bale.
   The new twin-engine plane can carry 163 people. It features a
fully computerized flight-control system and went into service last
month with Air France and British Airways.
   The plane is manufactured by Airbus Industrie, a consortium of
European aircraft companies led by its French and German partners.
