<DOCNO> AP880626-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SolarDisturbances     06-26 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solar Disturbances,400</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Record Solar Disturbances Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunspot activity is increasing rapidly and,
during the next few years, could lead to the most intense solar
disturbances ever recorded, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration said Sunday.
   Intense disturbances on the sun can have serious effects on
Earth, including interference with broadcasting, damage to
sensitive electronic systems in satellites and disturbances in
electrical power and telephone transmissions.
   Some scientists also have speculated that activity on the sun
could affect the climate on Earth, an idea that has prompted
considerable controversy in the meteorological community.
   Changes in rainfall patterns have occurred roughly in parallel
with changes on the sun over the years. However, proving that the
two are connected has, so far, eluded science.
   Sunspots occur in cycles of approximately 11 years.
Climatologists have found slight variations in rainfall patterns in
the United States over periods of 11 years in the central and
western states and over 22 years in the eastern states.
   The current cycle began in September 1986 and already has seen
record rates of increase in sunspots and radiation from the sun,
according to Gary Heckman, head of the NOAA-Air Force Space
Environment Services Center in Boulder, Colo.
   The most active previous solar cycle occurred in 1958. Activity
on the sun is already at about the same rate as in that year, but
with somewhat more intensity.
   Heckman noted that in a typical cycle sunspots increase to their
maximum in about 4.3 years and then take some 6.6 years to decline
to a minimum again. But cycles with rapid increases, as in the
current case, have higher and earlier maximum levels.
   Sunspots themselves do not affect the Earth, but are used as
indicators of other solar activity which does, such as solar flares
and geomagnetic storms, bombarding the Earth with radiation.
   Among the potential problems associated with an increase in
solar activity, according to Heckman, are:
   _Increasing activity by the aurora borealis or northern lights
(also the aurora australis, or southern lights, in Antarctica).
   _Interference with some kinds of radio communications and
broadcasts.
   _Disturbances in electrical power transmission systems,
pipelines and long-line telephone networks.
   _Damage to satellites' electronic systems.
   _Altered orbits of some satellites.
   _Radiation hazards to astronauts and aircraft passengers at high
altitudes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880626-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-EastBloc     06-26 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-East Bloc,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pontiff Reaches Out to Eastern Europe's Catholics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has used his Austrian
tour to reach out to those nearby Roman Catholics whose Eastern
bloc countries he has not been able to visit.
   While most attention on the five-day trip has focused on the
pope's remarks about Jews and the Holocaust, John Paul has also
been looking to millions of Catholics in Yugoslavia, Hungary and
Czechoslovakia.
   On Saturday, about 20,000 Yugoslav Catholics crossed the border
to the nearby Austrian town of Gurk for an outdoor Mass. The day
before, the pope said Mass for 80,000 Catholics, mostly Yugoslavs
and Hungarians, in the town of Trausdorf near the Hungarian border.
   The pope has visited Poland, his Communist homeland, three times
since he became head of the Roman Catholic Church in 1978. But so
far, Communist governments have imposed barriers that have kept him
from visiting millions of Catholics in Czechoslovakia, Hungary,
East Germany, Yugoslavia and the Soviet Union.
   Czechoslovak Catholics in particular have been in conflict with
Communist authorities, who until this year had not permitted any
new bishops in their country since 1973. Earlier this month, Prague
authorities finally allowed three new ones.
   The estimated 20,000 Yugoslav Catholics joined about 40,000
Italians and Austrians for the outdoor Mass on Saturday in Gurk.
   ``You all give testimony of the power of Christian faith to
overcome boundaries,'' John Paul said. ``Coming from several
cultures, you as the people of God speak the one language of common
belief.''
   ``Unfortunately today in Europe, even in your regions, the
ancient roots of faith are threatened in various ways,'' the
pontiff said, changing briefly from German to Italian in his homily.
   He continued: ``Christians must, however, react as a community
to this challenge. They must unite even more and stay even closer
together.''
   On Friday, he said his Mass for the 80,000 Catholics, mostly
Yugoslavs and Hungarians, in Trausdorf. Several hundred Poles and
several dozen Czechs also were on hand.
   Addressing the local Austrian Catholics, the pontiff said:
``This diocese and its bishop are well aware of their function as a
link in particular with the peoples of Eastern Europe.''
   ``You are ready to cultivate contacts with them and to share
with them, materially and spiritually,'' he said. ``Must not the
salvation Christ has given us again be spread to the farthest
bounds of Europe?''
   Some Austrian newspapers hailed the Mass as a major gesture
toward Eastern Europe.
   ``Trausdorf: A Signal for the East Bloc,'' trumpeted Vienna's
Kleine Zeitung daily newspaper in its Saturday editions.
   Other newspapers, though, felt that the pontiff had kept his
remarks deliberately low-key, possibly in hope of not upsetting any
chances he may have of visiting any new Eastern European countries.
   ``He overcame barriers by not putting up any,'' said the
conservative Die Presse daily newspaper of Vienna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
