<DOCNO> AP880626-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Furlough Bjt   06-26 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Furlough, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Furlough Program At Center Of Dukakis-Bush Crime
Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Republican George Bush wages an aggressive
effort to portray Michael Dukakis as a liberal who is soft on
crime, the man at the center of the vice president's pitch is
behind bars in a Maryland prison.
   Convicted murderer and rapist William Horton Jr. is as much a
part of the debate over crime this presidential campaign season as
the opposite views on the death penalty espoused by the two
candidates.
   Bush now mentions Horton by name, in campaign rhetoric laced
with attacks on a Massachusetts furlough program that allowed
Horton to be released from prison although he was serving a life
sentence for murdering a 17-year-old boy. In 1987, during his 10th
furlough, Horton fled to Maryland, twice raped a woman and
assaulted her fiance.
   ``I think Governor Dukakis owes the people of the United States
an explanation,'' Bush said last week in Illinois. ``What did the
Democratic governor of Massachusetts think he was doing when he let
convicted first-degree murderers out on weekend passes?''
   A day earlier, Bush was told of Dukakis' statement that 45
states and the federal prison system offer some form of furlough.
The vice president responded that ``none, except Massachusetts, had
furlough programs for first-degree murderers.''
   But, according to several correctional associations and
publications, at least 16 states offer furloughs to first-degree
murderers. Massachusetts no longer is among them: Dukakis
reluctantly signed a law banning first-degree lifers from furloughs.
   ``Ralph Waldo Emerson said that foolish consistency is the
hobgoblin of little minds,'' Dukakis said when he signed the bill
in April. ``I try to listen; I try to learn.''
   Since the Massachusetts program began in 1972, 117,700 furloughs
were granted to 10,553 inmates. Of the 426 escapes, 11 occurred
during the 4,908 furloughs granted to first-degree murderers.
   ``Massachusetts actually had a pretty good record,'' said Brian
Bemus, a researcher at the National Institute of Corrections data
center in Boulder, Colo.
   Bush has amended his attack on the furlough program, accurately
saying in recent days that Massachusetts, until April, had the only
furlough program in the nation for inmates sentenced to life
without parole.
   Campaign aides say the vice president will continue his attack.
   ``He finds this program of furloughing murderers with no-parole
sentences represents the worst sort of approach to crime,'' Bush
spokeswoman Alixe Glen said Friday. ``The furlough issue is
important because it shows how Dukakis' record on crime contrasts
with the vice president's positions. As this issue has been
elevated, I think the American people are shocked at the Willie
Horton example.''
   Faced with growing criticism from Bush and increased media
attention on the furlough program, the Dukakis camp has fired back
with national furlough statistics showing the Massachusetts
furlough-escape rate is below average and by invoking the name of
Bush's boss, President Reagan, who as governor of California
supported furloughs even after two convicts killed people while on
furlough in the early 1970s.
   Like Reagan, Dukakis inherited the furlough program from a
governor of the opposition party.
   ``These are part and parcel of all kinds of responsible
correction programs,'' says Dukakis, who has spent much of the past
week defending the Massachusetts program, largely by citing a 14
percent drop in crime in his state over the past five years.
   ``Our view is that the vice president is trying, through the
furlough issue, to obscure the facts,'' Dukakis issues adviser Tom
Herman said in an interview. ``The fact is that while crime is
going up nationally, crime is dropping dramatically in
Massachusetts.
   ``He also is using it to obscure the unenviable crimefighting
record of the Reagan-Bush administration,'' said Herman, who spent
much of last week researching furlough programs. ``Bush is reacting
to this issue in a sense that tells me he's running scared.''
   If the criticisms continue, aides say, look for Dukakis to adopt
the strategy he used when former rival Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee criticized the Massachusetts furlough program during the
primary campaign.
   ``Al, the difference between you and me is that I have to run a
criminal justice system. You never have,'' Dukakis said during an
April debate in New York. That kind of response to Bush would fit
in with the Dukakis strategy to attempt to characterize Bush as a
do-nothing vice president.
   Among corrections officials and criminoligists, furloughs are
considered an effective rehabilitation tool.
   ``Most knowledgeable correctional workers, prisoners and others
interested in work furlough see it as a progressive correctional
program,'' said a 1975 review of one program _ that of
then-California Gov. Reagan.
   ``There is no way that we're ever going to be 100 percent able
to give you a program where the parole board or the furlough
program has fallen down,'' said Professor James Fox of Northeastern
University's School of Criminal Justice.
   He also questioned the relevance of the furlough issue in
presidential politics.
   ``If freeing a murderer on furlough is the issue, then it's moot
because murder is, except for in rare cases, a state crime and the
president doesn't really deal with murderers,'' Fox said.
</TEXT>
