<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionProblems     06-26 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Problems,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Confront Problems As Clock Toward Convention Winds Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With less than a month to go before the
Democratic National Convention, incomplete housing arrangements
threaten the party's hopes for a smooth kickoff to its biggest
media event of the year.
   But some of those who will be covering the gathering say they
don't expect problems severe enough to be noticed by the Democrats'
real audience _ the millions of American voters who be will
watching or reading about the convention across the country.
   While the city has been sprucing up for the visitors, the host
committee and party organizers sometimes have been slow to provide
information to reporters and others who have to make arrangements
of their own, said Jane Maxwell, Cable News Network's vice
president for special events.
   But she said the problems probably won't affect the picture CNN
presents to the public.
   ``The fact is we have to be ready for the event because they
aren't going to delay it for us,'' she said.
   Ms. Maxwell and her counterpart at CBS, David Buksbaum, gave
convention organizers good marks for helping with television
coverage. The complaints from news organizations center on
off-the-floor matters, especially housing.
   ``Hotel rooms are really a problem,'' said NBC producer Phil
Alongi, who said the network has received only a few rooms in
downtown hotels.
   ``I just can't find enough words to describe how much trouble
they're going to be in,'' said Mary Pat Clark, the office manager
of the Los Angeles Times' Washington bureau, who said housing
arrangements started much later in Atlanta than in previous
convention cities.
   The convention has fared better on other fronts.
   A newly opened rapid rail station at Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport means delegates can reach downtown in 15
minutes for an 85-cent fare. Those traveling the route by car will
have to contend with ongoing construction on the I-75-85 ``downtown
connector,'' but the disarray has not proved a major problem to
larger conventions.
   The city long ago gave up on Mayor Andrew Young's initial hope
that a renovated Underground Atlanta entertainment district could
open in time for the convention, but delegates will be offered
excursions on a steam-powered train line newly extended to the
Stone Mountain tourist attraction.
   Once the Atlanta Hawks were defeated in the National Basketball
Association playoffs, workers began building the huge stage,
network anchor booths and other fixtures of the convention at the
Omni Coliseum.
   ``It does seem finally to be coming together and more and more
of the details are slowly being revealed,'' said David B. Cooper,
associate editor of the Akron Beacon Journal and deputy convention
manager for Knight-Ridder Inc.
   Bob Murphy, a senior producer at ABC, said, ``We are on schedule
and there's nothing new from any other convention in dealing with
Democrats. They always appear to be somewhat disorganized in the
very beginning and then everything seems to fall in place.''
   Murphy said his network has rejected some of its assigned hotel
rooms because they are not close enough for key personnel.
   Some disputes were inevitable because some of the convention
hotels are located in the suburbs. Ms. Clark, who has worked on six
previous political conventions, said the situation was made worse
when organizers started making assignments much too late.
   Overbooking can be expected, she said, leading to a last-minute
scramble for canceled rooms. In Atlanta's case, she said, ``They're
going to have chaos.''
   And if maintenance workers strike the Atlanta Hilton & Towers,
as threatened in a long labor dispute, delegates from California,
Tennessee, Louisiana and Wyoming will be looking for new rooms.
   Convention spokeswoman Ruth Berry said hotel managers were told
in an April letter it would be July 11 before housing plans could
be finalized. She said only three of 107 managers responded with
questions about the arrangements.
   But one hotel manager who asked not to be named said, ``I can't
even get the Democrats to return a phone call. I've been calling
them for a week. That tells me that they can't tell me anything
because they're still confused.''
   ``I think it's fair to say we're behind schedule,'' Ms. Berry
said. ``We're in a different situation than San Francisco (site of
the 1984 convention). San Francisco had a lot more downtown hotel
rooms. But everybody will get one.''
   Wally Podrazik, co-director of media arrangements and facilities
and a veteran of three previous conventions, says everything will
be ready in time.
   Podrazik took over in late May, succeeding Bob Ferrante who was
dismissed after complaints that the media effort was disorganized.
   ``I was coming in just about when people were giving final
answers or close to final answers'' on convention logistics,
Podrazik said.
   Maurice Johnson, superintendent of the U.S. Senate Press
Photographers' Gallery, said efforts to coordinate coverage have
been hampered because of delays in receiving plans for
photographers.
   Johnson, who has worked on four previous Democratic conventions
in his current position and covered others as a news photographer
dating back to 1948, said, ``They're usually hectic, but this is a
lot worse than previous ones.''
   
</TEXT>
