<DOCNO> AP880626-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Impact Bjt   06-26 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Impact, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Doesn't Expect Immediate Slowdown in Contract Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense industry fears that the
investigation of fraud and bribery in Pentagon contracting will
cause a slowdown in contract awards and new layers of oversight,
but the Pentagon says it doesn't expect that fallout any time soon.
   ``We are at least weeks, if not months, away from the kind of
evidence which would point to looking at the acquisition process
(for an overhaul),'' says Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief
spokesman.
   In the meantime, the process of awarding contracts ``has not
ground to a halt,'' Howard said. ``It couldn't if we continue to
stay in business.''
   However, industry officials were nearly unanimous in their
concern about the impact of the probe.
   The investigation ``is very bad news for all of us because of
the effect it's going to have on the reputation of the industry in
total, and because of the stimulus it will provide for additional
regulations and oversight,'' W. B. Jones, a vice president of the
Grumman Corp., said last week.
   ``We'll get regulations and stipulations on what consultants may
do,'' said Joseph Campbell, an aerospace analyst for the Paine
Webber Group Inc.
   Larry McCracken, manager of media relations for Raytheon Corp.,
said, ``Most people believe the procurement process will probably
slow down a bit because of new people being moved into some of the
positions (at the Pentagon). The whole process,'' McCracken said,
``will just be a more cautious process.''
   Several companies are also worried that existing contracts will
be canceled because of evidence of wrongdoing and ``they may have
to rebid projects already under way,'' said Herbert C. Hetu, a
spokesman for the Aerospace Industries Association.
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger, meanwhile, said
Sunday that an earlier study of Pentagon contracting found that
contractors already are overaudited and often don't have the
opportunity to make adequate profits. And he expressed a fear that
the scandal could lead to cuts in defense spending.
   ``I certainly hope that this is not used as an excuse by the
professional Pentagon bashers for cutting out enough funding for
the defense of this nation,'' Weinberger said on NBC-TV's ``Meet
the Press.''
   The investigation of defense fraud, started by the Naval
Investigative Service nearly two years ago and now directed by the
Justice Department, surfaced on June 14 when FBI agents served more
than three dozen search warrants around the country.
   The warrants named some of the nation's largest defense
contractors along with industry consultants and Defense Department
workers. Among the most prominent of the consultants was Melvyn
Paisley, who until April 1987 was an assistant secretary of the
Navy.
   Justice Department officials say the inquiry centers on
allegations that Pentagon executives took bribes from private
military consultants who were selling classified contract
information to their corporate clients.
   To date, the Pentagon's only official response to the
investigation has been to reassign six officials of the Navy and
Air Force to other jobs pending the outcome of the investigation.
   The reassignments, including a man holding the fairly
high-ranking position of deputy assistant secretary of the Navy,
are not of sufficient number to create important gaps in the
procurement bureaucracy, the services said last week.
   ``We just don't foresee any type of impact on the award of
contracts because of these moves,'' said Lt. Janet Mescus, a Navy
spokeswoman.
   Howard and other officials say the scandal is simply too young
to directly affect the awarding of contracts. With about 60,000
contracts being awarded every work day _ 15.3 million contracts
totaling $156.5 billion were distributed in fiscal 1987 _ there is
a momentum that is not easily arrested, they said.
   ``This is a massive organization,'' Howard said. ``It has 50,000
people writing contracts or involved in the contractual process.''
   Another Pentagon executive agreed: ``There's no impact on
awards. You can't stop buying F-A-18s when the Navy needs F-A-18s
for its carriers. It doesn't work that way.''
   Industry officials counter that if they are premature with their
fears, the handwriting is on the wall. Indeed, many say they are so
concerned that they don't want to talk about the scandal for fear
of fanning publicity.
   One executive, demanding anonymity, explained: ``Here I am,
staring at more competition to begin with because the defense
budget is being cut; facing reduced (profit) margins because of
regulatory changes, and you want me to talk about a probe that is
spreading the impression the entire defense industry is crooked. No
thanks.''
   Underscoring the pressures being produced by the investigation,
a Senate committee flirted briefly last Friday with legislation
that would have allowed the government to suspend payments to
defense contractors under investigation in the case.
   The committee decided such action would be premature, but there
were predictions the matter would arise again on the Senate floor.
</TEXT>
