<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   06-26 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kabul Airport Fire Destroys Eight Soviet Jet Fighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western sources said Sunday that a
fire at the Kabul airport in Afghanistan destroyed eight Soviet jet
fighters and may have been the result of an attack by Moslem
guerrillas.
   The diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
reports coming in late Saturday said eight Soviet Su-25 jet
fighters exploded one after the other at the northwest end of the
airport.
   A telex report from one Western embassy called it ``one of the
largest Soviet air losses in the war.''
   The sources said their counterparts in the Afghan capital first
heard of the fire Friday morning. The explosions and tracer-like
eruptions indicated the fire also set off some ammunition, they
said.
   ``It looks like a (guerrilla) attack,'' said one Western
diplomat in Islamabad.
   He said reliable sources in Kabul reported seeing two incoming
rockets, likely fired by insurgents, hit Theo Oga Airport about two
hours after the fire was first noticed.
   Diplomats said the Saturday reports indicated the Soviet planes
were parked almost two miles away from where the rounds hit Friday.
   Soviet and Afghan government forces were fighting U.S.-backed
guerrillas just west of the airport, on the northern outskirts of
the capital, diplomats said.
   The fire has shut down activities at the airport, the sources
said. They said no fixed-wing aircraft have been seen landing there
since the fire began, and that one Soviet Il-76 transport plane was
seen being diverted on approach.
   However, at least one commercial flight of the Afghan airline
Ariana arrived in New Delhi from Kabul on Saturday, passengers
said. Civil and military planes use the same runways at Kabul but
it was not immediately known how many Ariana planes are using the
airport.
   Earlier reports had described heavy military traffic at the
airport as Soviets stepped up the resupply of Afghan government
troops when the Red Army started its nine-month withdrawal from
Afghanistan on May 15.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979 to back
the Kabul government in its war with Afghan rebels. They began
withdrawing under an accord signed April 14 in Geneva.
   Guerrillas claimed to have launched rocket attacks on the
airport last week but not on Friday.
   In another development, Afghan and diplomatic sources reported
rebels shot down an Afghan transport plane on June 16 near the
embattled eastern garrison town of Khost.
   Diplomatic sources said Afghans put the casualty toll at 30 to
40 but were not able to confirm whether all the victims were
military.
   The sources said the incident has reduced the number of
nighttime flights into Khost. The flights have been the only means
to resupply the garrison, which is surrounded by guerrillas near
the Pakistan border.
   Guerrillas have taken dozens of communist posts in eastern
Afghanistan since Soviet and Afghan government troops began
redeploying after the Geneva accord.
   Under the agreement, the Soviets began the nine-month withdrawal
on schedule on May 15. The Soviet-backed Kabul government said only
Soviet troops, not Soviet military advisers, will leave.
</TEXT>
