<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Protest     06-26 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Protest,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Women's Demonstration Against Islamic Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Sunday used sticks to break
up a march by women protesting a decree that made Islam the supreme
law of Pakistan, a witness said.
   The witness said that in the eastern city of Lahore, police
confronted about 150 women demonstrating against the law, which
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq put into effect June 15 in a
televised address to the nation.
   The witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said police
lashed out with batons.
   The decree makes Islam ``the supreme law of Pakistan,'' but it
will not affect the rights of non-Moslems or the country's business
contracts with other nations, Zia said.
   
   The women said they feared the measure would negate Moslem laws
introduced in 1961, which acknowledge a woman's right to divorce as
well as to demand the registration of marriages and divorces.
   Witnesses said the protesters, who later held a sit-in, also
condemned the United States for suporting ``the dictator of
Pakistan.'' Police arrested six of the protesters.
   On May 29, Zia, who is also army chief of staff, fired his
entire civilian government and dissolved the National Assembly. He
charged the elected ruling bodies with failure to implement the
Islam codes.
   Zia hinted that elections would be announced within 90 days, but
he hasn't set a date.
   In the southern port city of Karachi, the head of Pakistan's
opposition People's Party, Benazir Bhutto, warned the president
against postponing elections.
   ``This time you (Zia) cannot escape elections,'' Bhutto said in
front of a rally of thousands.
   In 1979, Zia ordered the hanging of former prime minister
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, Benazir's father, after overthrowing him in a
1977 military coup.
   Members of Bhutto's People's Party were among the demonstrators
in Lahore.
</TEXT>
