<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-DirtPoor Bjt   06-26 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Dirt Poor, Bjt,0864</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poorest of the Poor Scorched By Drought, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNICA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmhand Gus Daniels toils for minimum wage
on a cotton and soybean farm, scraping by during the searing
drought in a tin-roofed sharecropper's house that has no running
water and not even an outhouse.
   ``It's hot enough out there to make a man quit,'' said Daniels,
41, on the fifth straight day of 100-plus-degree temperatures in
the upper Mississippi delta.
   ``You don't want to go out in the heat. But when it's time to go
to work, I'll be there,'' Daniels said Saturday. ``We survive the
best we can in this county down here. Can't do nothing but
survive.''
   The worst drought in 50 years, coupled with a combination punch
of record high temperatures, hits everyone in Tunica County, one of
the poorest areas in the country. The heat always seems the hottest
for those at the bottom of the bottom, but they shrug it off.
   ``I was raised in the hot weather,'' said Daniels, the son of a
sharecropper who also was the son of a sharecropper.
   Daniels earns $3.35 an hour to work a sweat-soaked, 12-hour
shift that begins at 7 a.m. daily.
   Although sharecropping has virtually vanished, some of the
shabby shanties remain. Daniels lives with his wife and 6-year-old
daughter in an unpainted wooden shack consisting of two rooms, a
kitchen and a bedroom.
   Flattened cardboard boxes serve as wallpaper. The toilet is a
bucket or a space behind a barn. Water is hauled from town a mile
away. The family pays no rent but has to pay the electric bill.
   The house has one fan; air conditioning is a fantasy. Nothing is
insulated, and the paneless windows have screens patched together
with tape.
   On a rare day off Saturday, Daniels sharpened tools and tinkered
with his truck in the front yard, which adjoins a cotton field. The
farm he works, which he calls a plantation, is irrigated and has
weathered the hot, dry spell so far.
   ``It got so dry, the boss was laying off. I guess he felt sorry
for us,'' said Daniels, listening to the blues on his pickup's
radio.
   In northern Mississippi, clay soil that should be as black as
buckshot pellets looks white because the moisture's been baked out
of it. Dust clouds rise behind tractors like smoke from a fire,
then settles on long, straight rows of crops struggling to survive
on lands as flat as a tabletop.
   At the end of a dusty dirt road in the middle of a cotton field
outside of Tunica, Jerlean Simmons hung a load of laundry in the
wilting midday sun.
   ``It's too hot for anything,'' said Mrs. Simmons, 35.
``Everything's drying up. I know it's affecting the farmers. I
couldn't even raise a garden. It burned up.''
   The hum of three electric fans droned from the old
sharecropper's house, consisting of three bedrooms and a kitchen
topped by corrugated tin. It has no running water and no toilet.
Plastic sheets make do as window panes.
   Mrs. Simmons' 16-year-old daughter, also named Jerlean, worked
three days last week and four days the week before as a cotton
chopper.
   The job is as unglamorous as it sounds. For 10 hours a day at
the minimum wage, laborers chop weeds with hoes along cotton rows.
   ``It's the only kind of work we can find to do,'' said Mrs.
Simmons. ``It's the only way to make a living when you ain't got no
job. Jobs is hard to find.''
   About 200 hands work as choppers in Tunica County, where cotton
is still king but the per capita wage is $6,800, about 30 percent
lower than average in Mississippi. But the dry weather even puts a
crimp in that grueling endeavor.
   ``It's so hot and dry, the weeds aren't growing,'' said Owen
Bibb, a farmer who laid off 15 choppers on Friday because he didn't
need them anymore.
   Cotton farmers kill weeds with chemicals. But unless rain falls,
the chemicals don't do their job.
   ``It's been so dry, chemicals don't work very well. Choppers get
the escape weeds,'' said county agent Dwayne Wheeler.
   ``It's not glamorous work,'' Wheeler said. ``I did it for a
while. It didn't take me long to figure out I didn't want to do
that the rest of my life.''
   Five miles down the road from Tunica, at a crossroads near a
granary, sits Clayton. It's the home of the D&R One-Stop, a gas
station, grocery store, beer garden, pool hall and sandwich shop
under a shingled roof. Sweaty men sat outside on a wooden bench in
the unpaved parking lot, where an outdoor thermometer read 110
degrees in the shade.
   ``Everything's burning up,'' said a farmhand who identified
himself as Rock, sipping an icy drink after working the fields
until noon. ``It's hot as hell. If it don't rain, there ain't going
to be nothing for nobody to do. Right now, it's rough. All we can
do is look to the Lord.''
</TEXT>
