<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthResearch Bjt   06-26 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Research, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Criticizes Research on Medicare, Medicaid Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is making decisions about the $120
billion-a-year Medicare and Medicaid programs on the basis of
federal research that is often delayed or of poor quality, the
General Accounting Office reported Sunday.
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, said the Health Care
Financing Administration was producing reports that ``were often
not fully responsive to congressional needs, were frequently late
and were variable in their technical adequacy.''
   The GAO attributed some of the problems to the lengthy review
and revision process conducted by administration policy makers both
inside and outside the health field.
   More than 45 million elderly, disabled and poor Americans rely
on Medicare and Medicaid to pay for their health services. The
Health Care Financing Administration oversees the two programs.
   The financing administration also conducts research at the
request of Congress or the president when cutbacks or changes are
being contemplated, to determine their impact on health care.
Recent studies, for example, have examined the Medicare prospective
payment system for hospitals and state regulations on Medigap
policies that insure people for services uncovered by Medicare.
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Government
Operations subcommittee on human resources, said the GAO report
raises serious questions about how important decisions affecting
health care are made.
   ``If policies are made on the basis of inadequate or misleading
information, or if the information needed is not provided on time,
then we can expect health care to deteriorate,'' Weiss, who
requested the report, said in a statement.
   The GAO said concerns about the quality of Health Care Financing
Administration research had been expressed since 1980 by Congress,
congressional agencies, the Department of Health and Human
Services, and others. It said quality had not improved much in the
last eight years.
   Part of the reason, the GAO said, was that Congress was
mandating more and more studies while the administration was
reducing the health care agency's staff and resources.
   The GAO studied three areas and made the following comments:
   _Relevance. The office said that reports to Congress suffered
from a combination of vague mandates, lack of formal communications
between lawmakers and researchers, and administration reviewers who
deleted relevant information on the basis of policy considerations.
   _Timeliness. The GAO found that of 28 reports due before the
summer of 1986, 26 were delivered late or were still overdue. The
lateness was attributed primarily to a review-revision cycle
involving officials at the health care financing agency, the
Department of Health and Human Services and the Office of
Management and Budget. Reviews ``often have lasted for months or
even years,'' the agency said.
   _Technical quality of research. More than one-third of the
projects awarded by the health care financing agency in one year
were disapproved by review panels on the basis of technical
inadequacy, the GAO found. This was blamed on a flawed award
process and a finding that ``a technical perspective did not always
dominate reviews'' by the health care financing agency, the
Department of Health and Human Services and the Office of
Management and Budget.
   The deputy administrator of the health care financing agency,
Glenn Hackbarth, denied that his agency has been improperly
influenced by policy considerations.
   ``Obviously, on policy issues, we do have a policy perspective
that we advocate. I don't think that's unfair,'' he said. ``I do
not think there are instances where we have tried to mislead
Congress by deleting relevant, factual, technical information.''
   Hackbarth said that Congress, rather than the review process, is
to blame for tardy reports. He said lawmakers require long lists of
studies without considering the money or staff available to do them.
   ``It should be no surprise to anyone that there are more studies
than there are resources and the end result is late reports,'' he
said.
   Hackbarth admitted that his agency has sometimes awarded grant
money to projects that are technically weak, but said it has been
done when the agency had virtually no alternative.
   ``We can either not do any research on a pressing problem or we
can decide to go ahead with a proposal that is not technically
everything we would like it to be,'' he said. ``Sometimes we do the
latter and I think it is entirely defensible.''
   The GAO report recommended a number of steps it believes the
Department of Health and Human Services should take, among them an
assessment of whether health care financing agency has enough staff
and resources to handle the reports mandated by Congress and sought
by the administration. It also said the department should develop a
formalized review process to ensure timely delivery of reports, and
make sure there is better communication between researchers and
lawmakers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
