<1ST_LINE>r p AM-League-Debates     06-26 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-League-Debates,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>League of Women Voters Starting Postcard Campaign to Get Debates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The League of Women Voters is starting a
nationwide postcard-writing campaign to try to get the 1988
presidential candidates to agree to debate under its sponsorship.
   Two postcards, one addressed to Republican George Bush and one
to Democrat Michael Dukakis, are being sent to league members with
an accompanying letter from Nancy Neuman, chairwoman of the group's
education fund.
   ``The shameless attempt by the two parties to `steal' the
debates threatens more than the league,'' the letter said. ``It
threatens the voters.''
   The postcards urge the two likely nominees to commit to the
league's general election debates. The league is asking its members
to mail the postcards to the two candidates.
   The group has sponsored presidential debates since 1976, but
this year has been fighting with the Democratic and Republican
parties which are holding their own debates.
   Dan Schnur, a Bush spokesman, said, ``We will wait and see what
the two parties decide. We are not closing any options.''
   ``I know we are committed to the Democratic National Committee
and Republican National Committee debates,'' said Steve Akey, a
Dukakis spokesman. ``At this point that is all we have committed
to.''
   Both the league and the parties are proposing three debates for
the presidential candidates and one for the vice presidential
candidates.
   The league has announced debates in Birmingham, Ala.;
Minneapolis-St. Paul, Minn.; Boston and Los Angeles. The parties
announced debates in Annapolis, Md.; Winston-Salem, N.C.; Omaha,
Neb.; and Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
