<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Singleton     06-26 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singleton,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search For Clues In Singleton Home Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were scrutinizing remnants of a crude
homemade bomb tossed at the home of rapist Lawrence Singleton's
brother, but had no idea Sunday who hurled the explosive in a
normally quiet Tampa suburb.
   Walter Singleton and his wife, Dianne, were alone in their house
when the bomb exploded Saturday night in their front yard, about 30
feet from the front door, said Hillsborough County sheriff's
spokesman Debbie Carter. They were uninjured.
   Bomb squad experts were looking for fingerprints and other clues
Sunday on bomb bits picked out of the lawn, she said.
   ``Our bomb squad has the fragments that are left; we think it
was a homemade device,'' she said. ``We found pieces of cardboard
and duct tape. We're processing them so hopefully we'll be able to
tell something from that.'''
   There were no arrests by midday Sunday, and no one saw the bomb
tossed.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker,
chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead in a
ditch southeast of San Francisco in 1978. The girl survived.
   A 60-year-old former merchant seaman who grew up in Tampa,
Lawrence Singleton spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a
California prison.
   He completed a year-long probation and is now free to live where
he pleases. During his probation, he was forced to live in a
trailer on the grounds of San Quentin prison grounds because of
bitter protest in several communities that were proposed as homes
for him.
   The blast left an impression about four feet across in the yard,
but no damage to the house that Singleton listed with state
officials as his Florida address, said sheriff's Maj. Ron
Poindexter.
   ``At first we thought it was a lightning bolt, then we looked
out of our window and saw smoke,'' said neighbor Harrie Grimes.
   Neighbors happened to see a red vehicle in the area, but
authorities don't know if it was the same one from which the bomb
was hurled, Ms. Carter said.
   Since Lawrence Singleton registered his brother's address with
the state, neighbors have been frightened and upset. A local
businessman and a radio station have each offered Singleton $5,000
if he will pack up and go anywhere else.
   Walter Singleton says his brother lives ``about two hours away''
from here, but refuses to say exactly where.
   Ms. Carter said it was unclear if the bombing would further
upset residents of the Forest Hills neighborhood.
   ``It's too early to tell if this is going to add fuel to the
fire, so to speak,'' she said. ``We have patrols in the area that
make periodic checks on Mr. Singleton's home.''
</TEXT>
