<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EmbattledEditor Bjt   06-26 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embattled Editor, Bjt,0822</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Bring Rare Criminal Libel Charges Against Newspaper
Editor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago, an editor besieged by Jim
Fitts' letters to his newspaper suggested that the retired
agriculture teacher start up his own publication to voice his
opinions.
   Fitts took the advice, and today his fledgling weekly is in the
midst of a legal battle involving First Amendment rights.
   Fitts, the 62-year-old editor of Williamsburg County's The Voice
newspaper, not only stirred up the political powers that be in this
poor, rural county of some 40,000 people. His denunciation of two
politicians and subsequent arrest on criminal libel charges caught
the attention of journalists around the country.
   Fitts has gone to jail once and could go again for expressing
his opinion in a newspaper. He awaits word Monday on whether he has
been indicted by a Williamsburg County grand jury on criminal libel
charges.
   If indicted and convicted, he faces a fine of up to $5,000 and a
year in jail.
   ``Clearly, we've got a political commentator making a political
statement about two politicians,'' said Jane Kirtley, executive
director of the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in
Washington. ``It seems to me that punishing someone for speaking is
not an American concept.''
   But Fitts' targets see something more in the caustic column he
wrote before the June 14 primary elections.
   State Rep. B.J. Gordon and state Sen. Frank McGill say Fitts'
attacks, in which he accuses them of stealing and corruption
without offering evidence, are lying, hurtful shots that deserve to
be punished.
   ``Freedom of the press is not to go around with freedom and
accuse people of committing crimes,'' Gordon said.
   The two politicians have brought what is believed to be only the
fourth criminal libel suit in South Carolina in 40 years, and the
first in the nation since 1984.
   Although civil libel cases are not unusual and often result in
the awarding of monetary damages to the aggrieved party, criminal
libel cases are rare because they can send a journalist to jail.
   Fitts, who spent 13 years as an agriculture teacher in Dillon
and North Myrtle Beach and 20 years as Clemson University's
agricultural extension agent in Williamsburg County, retired in
1986 and began sending letters to the county's only newspaper over
a controversial school board issue.
   After a while, he said, the editor suggested Fitts needed his
own paper to publish his opinions.
   ``I said, `That's a good idea; I hadn't thought about that,'''
he recalled in an interview Thursday.
   Roughly six months later, in January 1987, a new weekly began
rolling off the presses, and from the beginning it expressed Fitts'
outspoken style.
   ``I've always been opinionated,'' he said. ``I just have an
opinion and I have no problem sharing it.''
   He may have a problem sharing it for a while, however. The judge
who set his bond also put him under a gag order forbidding him to
discuss his arrest. He spent a weekend in jail under $40,000 bond
before he was released on his own recognizance.
   Gordon and McGill think Fitts crossed the line with a May 17
column, in which he wrote: ``I will say to you, without fear of
contradiction, if every black in Williamsburg County would start
stealing today and steal every day for the rest of their lives,
they could not steal as much as those two have stolen during their
time in power.''
   The column gave no specifics, and when asked what he thought
they had stolen, he said only that they had taken the pride of
people of Williamsburg County.
   He stressed that he was not apologizing for what he wrote but
acknowledged that he could have chosen his words better.
   ``I'm not trained as a journalist. I don't know how to polish
things,'' he said. ``Maybe if I had polished it, I could have
gotten it across better.''
   Fitts, who is black, has said that the dispute with the two
politicians is economic, not racial. Gordon is black and McGill is
white. The Voice, with a circulation of 2,300, has a largely black
readership.
   Despite what people like Kirtley say, Gordon and McGill's lawyer
said the criminal libel law is still a good one.
   ``I don't think the press has been fair in the matter,'' said
attorney Wallace Connor. ``I can understand ... they want to
protect themselves.
   ``There is a statute in this state against libel and slander.
They (the media) say that it's antiquated, but as long as it's a
law, it ought to be obeyed,'' Connor said.
   ``Also, if it's antiquated, the Ten Commandments are antiquated,
because they were written 5,000 years ago and it says `Thou shalt
not bear false witness,''' he said.
</TEXT>
