<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Pipeline     06-26 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Pipeline,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Scouts Help Drought-Stricken Willits To Lay Emergency Pipeline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Dirt Poor Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLITS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boy Scouts have rescued this isolated
city from the possibility that it would run out of drinking water
by the end of a drought-baked summer.
   A 2-mile-long, 8-inch pipeline, planned to be finished in a few
weeks, will link a Boy Scout camp reservoir with an undersized,
rundown municipal water system. The Scouts are letting the town
have the water for free.
   ``It gets a little thirsty around here when it doesn't rain,''
Alan Birket, city water supervisor, said last week.
   The Scout organization agreed to help last October after the
town of about 5,000 in a coastal valley 120 miles north of San
Francisco declared a state of emergency. Officials expected the
city's reservoir to run out by Thanksgiving.
   A convoy of trucks from a variety of government agencies hauled
in pipe loaned by the state. Forklifts from private companies
unloaded it. Workers from the state conservation youth corps began
clamping it together. All was at no cost to the ranching community
in Mendocino County.
   Then the rains came, so the pipeline was left unfinished.
However, only two-thirds of the normal 50 inches fell, not enough
to ward off fears that the city could run dry this summer.
   Now the city plans to finish the pipeline and begin pumping
water before its reservoir is drawn too far down.
   But some folks think the pipeline should already have been
completed in Willits, the only California city that's declared a
state of emergency because of the drought.
   ``People are always talking about it. It's not even finished.
It's just sitting out there,'' said Kelli Fuller, a 30-year-old
waitress at Mom's Place on Main Street, which is also U.S. 101.
   People aren't really worried, though, she added, plunking down
glasses of water for two customers who hadn't asked for them, in
violation of voluntary city conservation rules. She explained, with
a shrug, ``It's hot today.''
   Water conservation will shift from voluntary to mandatory
Friday, city Manager Bill Van Orden said. People who wash cars or
hose driveways can be fined $500. Sprinklers also will be shut off
at some city parks.
   ``If you waste water, you have neighbors telling on you,'' he
said.
   Voluntary measures, Van Orden said, have cut average daily water
usage significantly because ``the city officials asking for
cutbacks are residents' next-door neighbors, not people they don't
know _ like in larger cities.''
   ``We're all running around with dirty cars and not watering our
yards in the daytime,'' said Elin Crawford, an adult education
teacher.
   The drought has worsened water problems Willits already faced,
but the city is working to ensure that the headaches don't persist.
The city has secured $3.3 million in state loans to improve its
water system and expand its reservoir.
</TEXT>
