<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Refuseniks Bjt   06-26 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Refuseniks, Bjt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refusenik Protest Lasts 20 Minutes Before Leader Is Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jews demanding the right to emigrate
gathered on a Moscow street Sunday, but within minutes their
posters were ripped down and police took away the group's leader.
   Yuri Semenovsky and about 10 other Soviet Jews came to the
Arbat, a bustling pedestrian mall in central Moscow, to protest
legislation they say prevents them from leaving the country.
   Soviet officials say the only bar to emigration is knowledge of
state secrets, but Semenovsky and the others said they cannot leave
because of a law requiring documentation that they don't owe money
to relatives or ex-spouses.
   A law passed in August 1986 requires that the documentation be
provided by would-be emigrants' relatives. Semenovsky said Soviet
citizens have no legal way to make a relative provide such
information.
   ``The courts are no help,'' said the former mathematician, who
lost his job when he applied to leave the country more than two
years ago. ``They have been told not to get involved in cases
involving refuseniks. More than 200,000 Soviet Jews want to leave,
but can't.''
   At 4 p.m., Semenovsky and the others, members of a refusenik
group called the Poor Relatives, assembled in front of a building
on the Arbat. They taped four small posters on the wooden fence
that surrounds the building.
   One read: ``If you want to know the truth about refuseniks, and
not the usual lies and filth from the newspapers and Central
Television, read the informational leaflet from the `Poor
Relatives' Group.''
   Scores of Soviets assembled to scan the posters.
   Ten minutes after the posters went up, two men dressed in
civilian clothes ripped them down, walked away and threw them into
the trash.
   A water truck usually used to hose down Soviet streets passed
close to the group clustered around the posters, forcing them
closer to the wooden fence.
   ``It's the KGB,'' said Semenovsky.
   A police lieutenant came up to Semenovsky and asked him to
accompany him to a district court. Semenovsky asked if he was being
detained.
   ``I invite you to accompany me because of administrative
violations you have committed,'' the policeman said.
   ``What violations?'' Semenovsky asked.
   ``You know very well,'' the lieutenant said.
   Semenovsky refused to go, and the lieutenant left.
   A few minutes later, four uniformed police officers picked their
way through the scores of people who had gathered around the
demonstrators and grabbed Semenovsky.
   The policemen held the refusenik tightly under the arms as they
took him to a small green sedan. He was then driven away.
   Jewish emigration last month from the Soviet Union reached
1,145, its highest monthly total in seven years, but Jewish
activists say tens of thousands of Soviet Jews have had their
applications for an exit visa rejected.
   Semenovsky has said he cannot get an affadavit from his former
wife, Galina, that attests he does not owe her any money. He said
he tried three times to get Soviet courts to force her to give him
the document but that the courts refused.
   On Saturday, about 200 people refused to allow police to break
up a demonstration on Moscow's Pushkin Square by the Democratic
Union, a recently created group that wants to challenge the
political monopoly of the Communist Party.
   At least three people were detained by police at that protest.
Also Saturday, 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner and dissident Andrei
D. Sakharov joined former political prisoners and leading Soviet
intellectuals at an officially condoned rally in north Moscow to
demand a monument to the victims of Josef V. Stalin's purges.
   Authorities have announced they will take tough measures during
the nationwide Communist Party conference, which begins Tuesday, to
prevent unauthorized demonstrations in Moscow.
   ``I don't expect the party conference to deal with the problem
of Soviet Jews,'' Semenovsky said before his arrest. ``They have
said they will deal with ethnic relations, but not with our
emigration problem.''
</TEXT>
