<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YWCA-Men     06-26 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-YWCA-Men,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>YWCA Votes To Continue To Bar Men, Despite Legal Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Pene is cq in 16th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national YWCA, facing a court battle over a
Washington state chapter's decision to hire a man as a leader, has
voted to retain the all-female status it has held for 130 years,
its national president said Sunday.
   But the organization's board of directors postponed a vote on
whether to expel the Tacoma, Wash., chapter for hiring a man as
executive director, said President Glendora McIlwain Putnam.
   The chapter has sued to remain a part of the national
organization, which concluded its 31st national convention Sunday
at a downtown hotel.
   At the five-day meeting, an estimated 1,200 delegates from local
chapters across the country voted overwhelmingly to continue to
exclude men as full voting members, Ms. Putnam said.
   ``It is now more important than ever that the YWCA remain an
autonomous women's membership movement because of the serious
challenges which confront women in the areas of employment,
housing, child-care and poverty,'' she said.
   ``The YWCA's position is an affirmative response to inequity and
disparity which continue to be the rule rather than the
exception,'' she said.
   The Young Women's Christian Association in the United States was
founded in 1858 as an organization exclusively for women, partly to
address the problems of housing, poverty-level wages and
educational opportunities for young women who flocked to cities
during the Industrial Revolution.
   ``The fundamental focus of our organization has been the same
... the empowerment of women and girls ... making them more in
control of their lives,'' Ms. Putnam said.
   Under the group's constitution, men can participate as
associates, but not as full, voting members. The constitution also
says that executive directors should be full, voting members, said
spokeswoman Claire Carroll.
   Earlier this year, the Odgen, Utah, chapter became the first in
the country to lose its affiliation for allowing men to join as
full members. The chapter still has time to reconsider its action
before it is barred from using the YWCA name and logo, Ms. Putnam
said.
   Although recent court decisions have forced several formerly
all-male groups such as the Jaycees to admit women, Ms. Putnam said
she does not consider the YWCA policy discriminatory.
   Those earlier court rulings have been aimed at allowing women
into places ``where business is discussed,'' she said.
   ``We're not a marketplace issue. We don't come to the YWCA to
discuss business,'' Ms. Putnam said. Rather, the YWCA offers
services aimed solely at women, such as child-care, programs for
battered women and fitness classes, she said.
   ``Women need a place where they can be comfortable expressing
their problems, their fears, the way they face the world. They need
to discuss it with other women,'' she said.
   Pene Modahl, president of the Tacoma chapter's board of
directors, has said that hiring Alan Tiger as executive director
will not hurt that goal. She called him ``the best possible
candidate, who happened to be a man.''
   The Tacoma chapter filed suit June 10 in Pierce County, Wash.,
Superior Court seeking to bar the national board from expelling it.
   Ms. Putnam said she did not know when the board would vote on
whether to expel the chapter, but guessed that it might happen at
the next board meeting in October.
   Tiger, 36, who was hired in May, has vowed that the chapter will
retain its commitment to women. ``We have to ask ourselves, when in
the women's movement do we stop talking about men and women and
start to talk about humanity?'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
