<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   06-26 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Palestinian Leader's Sons; 8 Die In Renewed Beirut
Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb destroyed a Palestinian leader's
car Sunday and killed his two young sons in south Lebanon.
Dissident Palestinian guerrillas stormed a Beirut refugee camp in
clashes with Yasser Arafat's faction.
   Police said eight people were killed and 14 wounded as Arafat's
loyalists and Syrian-backed dissidents of Col. Saeed Mousa's
Fatah-Uprising faction fought with mortars and rockets in the
Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh shantytowns.
   By police count, 120 people have been killed and 516 wounded
since the power struggle for control of the camps in Beirut's
southern outskirts flared May 1.
   Police said artillery duels raged from dawn to dusk, when the
dissidents stormed Chatilla, capturing two of their four bases
seized by Arafat's Fatah faction a month ago.
   In the Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp outside the southern port of
Sidon, the two sons of Mohammed Mrad, a central committee member of
the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, were killed in the car bomb, police reported.
   They were identified as Ali, 13, and Mazen, 6. Police said the
bomb exploded when Ali turned on the ignition of his father's
Mercedes outside the family home.
   A Democratic Front statement charged that Israel's Mossad secret
service was behind the attack.
   Mossad has been blamed for the assassination in April of
Arafat's military commander, Khalil Wazir, in Tunis, and for the
killings of three of his senior officers in Limassol, Cyprus, in
February.
   In Beirut, two neutral guerrilla factions, the Democratic Front
and the Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
condemned Mousa's offensive as ``a total, systematic obliteration''
of the camps.
   The two groups in a joint statement called on Syria to
``intervene to put an end to the tragedy of the two camps.''
   Among Sunday's victims were two Syrian soldiers killed and
another wounded when a stray shell hit a checkpoint they were
manning near Bourj el-Barajneh, police reported.
   In the Beirut camps, witnesses said many residents fled during a
lull in fighting Saturday, packing their belongings and seeking
safety in Moslem west Beirut and south Lebanon.
   Mousa and other radical factions opposed to Arafat's policies
broke away from the Palestine Liberation Organization in a 1983
Syrian-backed mutiny.
   But the Democratic Front and the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine rejoined the PLO in 1987.
   The radical factions, opposed to any negotiations with Israel,
have bitterly condemned a statement by Bassam Abu Sharif, a close
Arafat aide, saying the PLO would recognize Israel in return for
direct peace talks.
   Information Minister Mohammed Salman of Syria said in Damascus
on Saturday that his country, the main power broker in Lebanon,
will not intervene ``materially'' to end the Palestinian feuding.
   Syria has thousands of troops enforcing security in west and
south Beirut. But troops who surround the two refugee camps have
made no move to stop the fighting.
   The battles have flared despite a reconciliation between Arafat,
the PLO chairman, and President Hafez Assad of Syria last April to
end a 5-year-old feud over who would control the Palestinian
movement.
   The movement seeks an independent homeland for Palestinians.
</TEXT>
