<HEAD>Kidnapped New York University Professor Freed In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with professor freed unharmed,
details. Picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Tamils, who ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five armed men on Sunday kidnapped a
New York University professor who was visiting his homeland to give
a lecture, but they freed him unharmed 5{ hours later, police said.
   Professor Ralph Bultjens, 48, was pushed into a car outside his
Colombo home by the gunmen and driven away at about 4 p.m., said
police, speaking on condition of anonymity. He was released at 9:30
p.m., police said.
   They declined to say where Bultjens was freed or whether any
ransom was demanded or paid.
   No reason for the episode was given. Police said initially they
did not know if the gunmen belonged to a militant group. Later they
refused to answer questions.
   According to a man who answered the telephone at Bultjens' home,
the professor was picked up by police after his release and taken
to police headquarters for brief questioning.
   The man, who refused to identify himself, said Bultjens was back
in his house about an hour after he was released but did not want
to come to the telephone.
   Bultjens was in his homeland to deliver a lecture in honor of
opposition leader Sirimavo Bandaranaike's late husband, Solomon,
who was the prime minister of Sri Lanka in the late 1950s.
   The lecture was scheduled for 5 p.m. at the Bandaranaike
Memorial International Conference Hall.
   Police said earlier they were investigating whether Tamil
separatists or militant Sinhalese were involved in the abduction.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, are waging a guerrilla war in Sri
Lanka for more autonomy from the majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who
control the government and military.
   Bultjens is neither a Tamil or a Sinhalese, but a member of the
minority ``Burgher'' community, made up of descendants of European
colonialists.
   The professor, a specialist in Asian studies, has been teaching
at New York University and the New School for Social Research in
New York City.
   His books include ``Tradition and Change in Modern Asia,'' ``The
Decline of Democracy'' and ``China After Mao.''
   Officials at the U.S. Embassy in Sri Lanka said they had no
information about the abduction.
</TEXT>
