<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Von Balthasar,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Theologian Dies Four Weeks After Being Named Cardinal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmitting a0771 to fix category code.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BASEL, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hans Urs von Balthasar, a prominent
Swiss theologian whom Pope John Paul II appointed cardinal four
weeks ago, died Sunday, church officials said. He was 82.
   Bishop Otto Wuest of Basel, in a brief statement, said that with
von Balthasar, ``one of the century's greatest theologians,''
passed away.
   Cause of his death was not immediately announced. Von Balthasar
had been scheduled to leave for Rome on Monday to be elevated to
his new rank along with 24 other newly designated cardinals.
   Von Balthasar was born Aug. 12, 1905 in Lucerne. After studies
in Switzerland, Germany, and France, he was ordained in 1936.
Except for a brief period as religious caretaker of Swiss students
in the 1940s, he concentrated on writing theological works.
   His 1952 essay, ``The Razing of the Bastions,'' was considered
to be one of the most important works published in preparation of
the Second Vatican Council.
   After the 1963-65 council, however, he wrote texts that were
critical of conciliar reforms. Since then, he had been rated as
pro-conservative.
   His nomination May 29 by Pope John Paul II came as a surprise to
many Catholics. He told reporters that as an obedient member of the
church he accepted the honor but added that he had asked the
pontiff several years ago to ``spare me any titles.''
   Von Balthasar held honorary doctorates from the University of
Washington in St. Louis, Mo., and from universities in Edinburgh,
and Muenster and Freiburg, West Germany.
   There was no word on survivors or when funeral services were
scheduled.
</TEXT>
