<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOD, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four American Jews said Sunday after
returning from Vienna that they were beaten by Austrian police when
they demonstrated against Pope John Paul II's meetings with
Austrian President Kurt Waldheim.
   The four made the charge during a news conference at Ben Gurion
Airport and also said they encountered anti-Semitism from some
Austrians during their weekend of protests in Vienna.
   Rabbi Avi Weiss of the Riverdale Synagogue in New York said he
and three students were beaten by police after they displayed a
large photograph of Waldheim in a Nazi uniform at Mauthausen, a
former concentration camp that the pope visited.
   ``We felt the pope's visit to Mauthausen was obscene ... after
he embraced Waldheim whose hands are red with Jewish blood,'' Weiss
said. ``This is an effort by the pope to de-Judaize the Holocaust.''
   Jewish groups have complained that the pope did not mention Jews
during his visit to the former Nazi camp, though he mentioned by
name some Catholics who died there.
   Jewish organizations have charged that Waldheim, who was in the
German army in World War II, was involved in war crimes.
   He denies the allegations but was barred from visiting the
United States after the U.S. government found evidence Waldheim was
involved in deporting Balkan citizens during the war.
   The men with Weiss were Eyal Shenzer, leader of a Jewish student
group, Jacob Davidson, head of the Jewish Student Organization of
North America, and Glen Richter, coordinator of the New York
City-based Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry.
   Hometowns for Shenzer and Davidson were not available.
   The four said they were cursed by Austrian citizens, some of
whom shouted ``Heil Hitler!'' when they demonstrated in Vienna. But
they said they also met Austrians who supported their views.
</TEXT>
