<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopsConference     06-26 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops Conference,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Move On From Nuclear Policy To AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Conference of Catholic
Bishops paused Sunday for prayer and relaxation before turning from
a debate on nuclear policy to one on the morality of teaching about
AIDS prevention.
   The Roman Catholic bishops held a public Mass Sunday morning and
scheduled a cookout and prayer session in the evening, a day after
approving a report that critics said was not strong enough in
urging disarmament.
   The report, approved by a strong voice vote of the approximately
280 bishops, opposed deployment of President Reagan's proposed
Strategic Defense Initiative. But it did not question the morality
of continuing research on the ``Star Wars'' missile defense system
within the bound of existing arms treaties.
   The bishops planned to end their four-day meeting at St. John's
University here Monday by taking up a paper that says teaching
about condom use would help prevent the spread of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   Some bishops oppose the statement, saying it will be
misinterpreted as condoning sex outside of marriage and the use of
artificial birth control, both contrary to Roman Catholic doctrine.
   The report on nuclear policy was approved as an update to the
bishops' 1983 pastoral letter on nuclear deterrence.
   The new report says, ``it is our prudential judgment that
proposals to press development of SDI do not measure up to the
moral criteria outlined in this report.''
   The report recommended that ``defense spending as a whole not
absorb a morally disproportionate percentage of the federal
budget.''
   The Rev. Thomas Gumbleton, auxiliary bishop of Detroit and the
head of the peace group Pax Christi USA, said he will continue to
work for the day when the bishops will say unequivocably that a
policy of nuclear deterrence is immoral.
   Gumbleton estimated that 50 to 60 of the bishops at the
conference feel the way he does. He said he and other bishops are
planning to issue their own statement on deterrence as a supplement
to the conference report.
   ``This report should not be the last word we say on nuclear
deterrence,'' said Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, archbishop of
Chicago, who chaired the committee that wrote the report.
   Benedictine Sister Ann Malerich, a member of Pax Christi, called
the report ``a step in the right direction.''
   ``Weapons aren't the answer,'' said Lucille Kuhl of Rochester, a
former coordinator of Pax Christi. ``They haven't solved a problem
yet. Why not try something else? Maybe we as a people have to be
more active in speaking out, rather than leaving it to our
bishops.''
   In other business Saturday, the bishops approved a campaign to
raise $20 million for retirement funds.
   Many orders can't afford to support older members because fewer
younger people are joining, and the cost of care is escalating. It
costs $400 million annually to care for the 40,000 men and women in
religious orders who are 70 years and older, according to Sister
Oliver Hudon, the head of the church's retirement project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
