<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Jazz-Fitzgerald     06-26 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jazz-Fitzgerald,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ella Fitzgerald Has New Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time Ella Fitzgerald sang at a jazz
festival here, she looked grandmotherly. This time, slim and sexy
in a small-waisted gray gown and a sparkling orange pants suit, she
was more in Lena Horne's category
   Saturday night's JVC Jazz Festival concert at Carnegie Hall
thrilled the audience, which seemed to be mostly in their 20s and
30s, musically as well. There were spontaneous standing ovations
and cheering at particularly telling bits of scat singing, growling
imitations of Louis Armstrong and triumphant high notes.
   The greatest novelty, which worked superbly, was the 70-year-old
singer's doing an oldie, ``Ain't Nobody's Business,'' to a disco
beat.
   Guitarist Les Paul, who has performed in Carnegie Hall 10 times
but never before sat in the audience, said: ``To me, she's an
instrument. She has that fantastic pitch.''
   The concert lasted 2{ hours, with Miss Fitzgerald singing except
for a brief segment after intermission by her trio, witty pianist
Paul Smith, her longtime bassist Keter Betts and new drummer Frank
Capp.
   She recently resumed performing after an absence of several
months, her health problems seemingly behind her. She was
hospitalized last year with diabetes and had coronary bypass
surgery in 1986.
   Her voice was strong throughout. She drew cheers and chuckles,
opening with ``Mr. Paganini,'' which begins, ``The concert was over
in Carnegie Hall.''
   She sang a lot of Duke Ellington, every song enjoyable _
``Caravan,'' ``Love You Madly,'' ``Sophisticated Lady,'' ``Squeeze
Me,'' ``Satin Doll,'' and a gently swung ``Take the A Train.''
Cheers followed her into the wings after ``I Can't Give You
Anything but Love,'' sung first in the style of Rose ``Chi Chi''
Murphy, then of Satchmo.
   Miss Fitzgerald never ``talked'' her songs or sat down on a
stool placed on the stage. In the second half, she sang seemingly
with more ease and open, warm tone. She also projected more feeling
than she sometimes has done in the past, especially in a Gershwin
medley.
   The audience, getting its first look at the slim pants suit
after intermission, whistled and cheered the lines ``Tell Lizzy
Arden to leave me alone; my shape is my own'' in her kickoff tune,
``The Lady Is a Tramp.''
   Miss Fitzgerald sang a bossa nova in Portuguese, did ``A House
Is Not a Home'' when somebody yelled a request for it, scatted and
did some dance steps to a swinging ``Stomping at the Savoy.''
   The audience didn't want to let her go, and she came back for
several encores _ ``You Are the Sunshine of My Life,'' ``Mack the
Knife'' and ``I Only Have Eyes for You.''
   She told the cheering audience she'd like to take them with her
to the next gig; the audience was ready to go.
</TEXT>
