<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     06-26 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Destroy Building, Palestinians Claim Soldiers Injecting
Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops declared a curfew in Gaza City
on Sunday, then blew up the second floor of a building from where
they believe a firebomb was thrown that burned two Israeli soldiers.
   In the West Bank, residents of the Al-Amari refugee camp told
reporters Sunday that Israeli soldiers injected at least two men
with an unknown substance to pry from them information about other
Palestinians.
   In Jerusalem, police uncovered several Palestinian guerrilla
units blamed for organizing protests and throwing firebombs at
police patrols and the car of Commerce and Industry Minister Ariel
Sharon, Israel radio reported.
   The report said the units were attached to the Syrian-backed
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical faction
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and the Moslem
fundamentalist Islamic Jihad.
   It did not say how many Palestinians were involved. A firebomb
missed Sharon's car on May 24.
   The explosions in Gaza City came in the wake of a firebomb
attack Monday night that seriously injured two soldiers driving
through the city in a jeep.
   An Arab reporter said he heard at least four blasts after the
army announced a curfew over loudspeakers, saying residents should
not be frightened if they heard explosions. He said he could not
see the blasts because he had to remain in his home under the
curfew order.
   The reporter said some damage was caused to the shops on the
first floor of the building and the army ordered residents to clean
up debris caused by the explosions.
   Earlier, he said, at least six shopkeepers were called to
military headquarters over complaints of firebombs thrown from
their buildings.
   At least 211 Palestinians have been killed since the Arab
uprising began Dec. 8 in the occupied territories. Four Israelis
have died.
   In the Al-Amari refugee camp, Nader Mahli, 24, said soldiers
seized him on Friday and injected him through a hypodermic needle
while asking him the names of stone throwers and members of the
Shabiba, a PLO youth movement.
   The army said it was investigating the report.
   Mahli said the soldiers took the syringe from a black attache
case, then blindfolded him. He said he felt the soldiers try to
inject him in the forearm, then do so on the inside of the elbow.
   ``The pain was exactly like any injection,'' he said. ``I
thought I was being poisoned. I was very afraid.''
   The young man showed two marks on his arm he said were from the
injections and deep scratches on his upper arm which he said the
soldiers also inflicted.
   One of the soldiers told him, ``After I inject you, you will
tell me everything,'' Mahli said.
   Another Palestinian, Ismail Dahoud, said he was questioned along
with Mahli and saw the injection being given.
   Mahli said he had chills and a headache Friday night. The next
day he went to Maqaseed Hospital in east Jerusalem, but doctors
could not find anything wrong with him.
   A hospital official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Mahli had bruised veins from an injection, but it was impossible to
tell what substance he had been given.
   Masaad Jaber, a driver for the United Nations, said his
19-year-old son, Midhad, was also seized in the camp Friday by four
soldiers who gave him an injection while questioning him.
   Jaber said he sent his son to the home of an uncle and was
trying to find a house outside the Al-Amari camp.
   ``I don't want to live here anymore after what happened to my
son,'' he said.
</TEXT>
