<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     06-26 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Points Finger At Congress In Anti-Drug Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Sunday
accused Congress of inaction in the fight against drugs, but a
representative of Democrat Michael Dukakis immediately turned the
blame on the Reagan administration.
   In speeches at a conference of the Fraternal Order of Police,
Bush and Dukakis supporter Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., each
laid the blame for failing to quell the drug crisis at the other's
doorstep.
   Bush, the certain Republican presidential nominee, also said he
would be tough in prosecution of drug dealers and would convert
unneeded military bases into minimum security prisons. He said he
had no specific bases in mind but would expect his secretary of
defense to review the matter.
   On the drug issue, Bush said, ``Congress is full of rhetorical
heroes on the issue of drugs, but when it comes to law enforcement,
some of them go AWOL,'' short for absent without leave.
   He said Congress reduced the administration's Coast Guard budget
request last year by $72 million, and by $864 million over four
years.
   But DeConcini claimed it was the administration that did the
cutting and Congress that restored dollars for drug-fighting
efforts. He said the Reagan administration's 1988 budget sought a
$900 million cut in anti-drug funds, including money for Coast
Guard and Border Patrol interdiction efforts. It also included a 60
percent cut in drug prevention and education programs.
   DeConcini said Congress restored 70 percent of the funds and he
labeled Bush's claim of congressional laxity as ``just a bogus
argument.''
   In a prepared statement, DeConcini also accused Bush of personal
failure as head of the National Narcotics Border Interdiction
System.
   DeConcini said the panel ``was found to be an organization of
half-empty offices lacking organization'' and added that it
virtually ignored the air charters that are ``the most commmon
means of smuggling cocaine into southern Florida.''
   DeConcini said he was addressing the group as a surrogate for
Dukakis, who has sewn up the Democratic presidential nomination and
is spending a few days vacationing in Nantucket, Mass.
   In a news conference after his speech, Bush debunked a report
that his aides have zeroed in on Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas as the
leading candidate to become Bush's running mate.
   ``Nobody is authorized to peak in my behalf,'' Bush said of the
report in Sunday's New York Times.
   ``We have not begun the process in terms of lists,'' he said.
``There isn't a long list or a short list.''
   Dole, while campaigning for Bush on Saturday in Oregon, was
asked about chances he would be the running mate and said: ``If I
got the call, I'd say, `Mr. Vice President, let's talk,' but that
hasn't happened.''
   Discussing what he will look for in a running mate, Bush said,
``I want to have an inclusion of the vice president on things. That
suggests a certain philosophical compatibility, not on every single
issue, but a philosophical compatibility and a tempermental
compatibility ... so you're not looking over wondering if the vice
president is posturing and cutting up the president.''
   In his remarks to the police group, Bush called for: mandatory
testing of ``anyone responsible for the public safety,''
recriminalization of drug possession in states where it has been
decriminalized, the death penalty for drug kingpins and those who
commit drug-related murders, and continuation of the ``zero
tolerance'' policy aimed at users of drugs in even small amounts.
</TEXT>
