<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Disarmament     06-26 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Disarmament Session Ends Without Final Document</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special General Assembly session on
disarmament ended in failure Sunday after delegates failed to adopt
a final document on nuclear arms reduction.
   The session ended Sunday morning after committee meetings could
not end differences in disarmament positions held by the Soviet
Union and developing nations and a more cautious approach backed by
the United States and some of its Western allies.
   The four-week session of the 159-member General Assembly, the
third in 10 years to focus on disarmament, cost the financially
ailing United Nations about $7.4 million.
   Delegates never voted on a final document. Committee delegates
decided not to attempt to pass a resolution without consensus.
   The General Assembly has no enforcement power over its
decisions. Delegates believed a final resolution adopted by
consensus, however, would carry the moral authority of expressing
the will of the world community.
   The United States and some of its Western allies opposed most
other nations on issues ranging from the U.S. space-based defense
program known as ``Star Wars,'' the monitoring of land-based
weapons, and a Soviet call for a joint U.S.-Soviet nuclear test ban.
   U.N. officials described the past week's committee debates as
``very intense and arduous.'' Some delegates said there were sharp
confrontations and shouting in at least one closed session.
   ``A certain country which should have important disarmament
responsibilities had insisted on its position. That was a major
reason that consensus was not achieved,'' said Chinese delegate Yu
Mengyia, referring to the United States.
   Soviet Union delegate Vladimir F. Petrovsky also noted that no
agreement was possible ``because of the actions of some states.''
   U.S. delegate Max Friedersdorf said the United States
``regretted very much that it had not been possible to achieve
consensus on the chairman's draft document, which had been
acceptable in large part to most delegations.''
   During the special session, the Soviets called for the
elimination of all nuclear weapons by the end of the century; troop
reductions of 500,000 soldiers each by the Warsaw Pact and NATO and
a ban on ``Star Wars.''
   Since the session began May 31, the United States was also at
odds with other positions favored by the Soviet Union, including an
expanded role for the United Nations in multilateral verification
of nuclear weapons and naval nuclear disarmament.
   The United States favored emphasis on conventional disarmament,
especially in Europe, where the Warsaw Pact is regarded as having
military superiority.
</TEXT>
