<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NOW-GenderGap     06-26 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NOW-Gender Gap,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Candidate Shirley Chisholm Says Gender Gap Could Disappear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``gender gap'' giving Democrat Michael
Dukakis an early lead over Republican George Bush might disappear
on Election Day, said former presidential candidate Shirley
Chisholm who warned that factors dividing female voters should not
be underestimated.
   Even though most women prefer Dukakis, the likely Democratic
nominee, it doesn't mean they will vote for him in November,
Chisholm told about 1,000 delegates to the National Organization
for Women conference in Buffalo.
   ``We're not as monolithic as led to believe,'' she said, noting
regional, economic and age difference among women voters.
   ``You constantly talk about being 53 percent of the vote, but if
you are unable to deliver that, you will be ignored,'' said the
former Brooklyn congresswoman who ran for president in 1972.
   Chisholm said there was similar talk of a gender gap in 1984
when the Republican ticket of Ronald Reagan and George Bush handed
the Democratic ticket of Walter Mondale and Geraldine Ferrao a
disastrous defeat.
   ``Many women, particulary southern women, couldn't identify with
Ferraro,'' she said. ``We've got ask why and learn from our
mistakes.''
   Part of the problem, she said, is that feminists are often
intolerant of opposing views.
   For the last decade, she said, women's right groups have judged
candidates mainly on their abortion postions. Women candidate who
are not pro-choice are often opposed, she said.
   ``You can't use one issue as a litmus test,'' she said. ``You
can't be that emotional about politics.''
   She said Democratic women should recognize that the party will
need to have a southerner or someone acceptable to southerners on
the ticket if it expects to win in November.
   ``You had better be prepared to accomodate the more conservative
views of southern women if you expect to maintain national
political power,'' she said. ``You can't afford to alienate them.''
   Chisholm campaigned for Jesse Jackson this year.
</TEXT>
