<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ValedictorianCharged 1stLd-Writethru a0822 06-26 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Valedictorian Charged, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0822,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valedictorian Charged With Killing Mother The Day He Was To
Graduate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes reference to Harvard in lead, CORRECTS 7th graf
``Friends and'' to show accused was to attend Univ. of Chicago sted
Harvard. Inserts one graf before final graf with detail of slaying.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager beat his mother to death
the morning he was to graduate as valedictorian of his class,
apparently because she was being overbearingly protective, police
said Sunday.
   ``He claimed his mother wouldn't give him any freedom,''
Detective Lt. Richard Clute said.
   William Shrubsall, 17, was in jail without bond Sunday after
police said he confessed to using a baseball bat to crush the skull
of his 56-year-old mother, Marianne, during an argument about 3
a.m. Saturday. The boy said his mother hit him first, Clute said.
   Shrubsall, who is scheduled to be arraigned Monday, was charged
with murder just 10 hours before he was to graduate with honors
from LaSalle High School.
   The graduation ceremony was held as scheduled Saturday, but with
no valedictory speech and no mention of the killing, said principal
Ralph Guerrucci.
   Guerrucci said school officials did not want to remind the class
of 250 students of the tragedy, ``but it definitely dampened the
day.''
   ``The graduates were understandaly upset. ... Obviously, they
don't want the day to be remembered by what happened to their
valedictorian,'' the principal said.
   Friends and neighbors reacted with disbelief that the crime
could have been committed by the handsome and popular teen-ager,
who hoped to become a lawyer and was to attend the highly selective
University of Chicago in the fall.
   ``You can't say anything bad about him. ... He was just
supernice,'' said Darlene Irish, a neighbor whose father had called
police. ``And his mom was one of those, `Can I do anything for
you?' persons. ... She was always helping.''
   A classmate, Larry Lang, said he'd never seen Shrubsall get
angry. Another classmate, Terry Adamec, said he couldn't believe
Shrubsall committed the crime.
   ``He had everything going for him,'' Adamec said. ``A class
valedictorian wouldn't do something like that. He was the smartest
guy in the whole school.''
   Shrubsall's attorney, Paul Cleary, said the boy and his mother
outwardly seemed to enjoy a good relationship, but had a history of
problems that led up to the killing.
   ``He made a detailed statement of that to police and it will
come out in court,'' Cleary said.
   The Buffalo News reported that Mrs. Shrubsall had physically
beaten the boy on previous occasions. The newspaper quoted an
unidentified source as saying that despite the boy's success in
school, his mother pressured him to do more.
   The newspaper report did not offer any evidence of beatings, or
discuss when or how often they may have occurred.
   Clute said the slaying occurred during an argument over
Shrubsall's returning late from his girlfriend's house two blocks
away.
   Mrs. Shrubsall had called the girl's home demanding that her son
return, and when he arrived she was waiting for him in the
driveway, police said.
   An argument continued inside with Mrs. Shrubsall threatening to
call the girl's parents. When she picked up the telephone, the boy
tried to stop her and she struck him in the face with the receiver,
police said.
   Police said the two had lived alone in their well-kept suburban
home since Shrubsall's father, William Sr., died in 1985.
</TEXT>
