<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-26 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temperatures Dive in Chicago; Hot, Humid Weather Continues in
South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures across the southern Great Lakes plunged 30 degrees
Sunday from the day-before record high readings, while hot and
humid weather smothered the South and thunderstorms poured heavy
rain over parts of Texas.
   Thunderstorms also extended from the southern coast of New
England across the mid-Atlantic states to Kentucky. Lightning
knocked out power throughout Cape Cod, Mass., for at least six
hours Sunday morning.
   Sunday afternoon readings across the southern Great Lakes, in
the 100s Saturday afternoon, were in the upper 60s and 70s, with
low humidity. Temperatures in Cleveland and Toledo and Findlay,
Ohio, all were 32 degrees cooler than at the same time Saturday.
   The South, however, was not so fortunate. Temperatures reached
100 degrees Sunday over portions of western Kentucky, Tennessee,
Alabama, Georgia and South Carolina.
   Several record high temperatures were set in the Tennessee
Valley. For the seventh day in a row, Huntsville, Ala., with a
record high of 99 degrees, set or tied a record high.
   In northwest Texas, more than 4 inches of rain fell Sunday
morning at Childress. In Real and Uvalde counties near San Antonio,
where 3 to 5 inches of rain fell Saturday, the National Weather
Service issued flash flood warnings.
   Thunderstorms were scattered from the Carolinas across the Gulf
Coast states to southeast Texas. Portions of the Rockies and the
Plateau region also reported thunderstorms.
   Besides the record in Huntsville, records for the date were set
in Apalachicola, Fla., at 96, and in Chattanooga, Tenn., at 101.
Records were tied in Glasgow, Mont., at 103 and Paducah, Ky., at
101.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 103 at Palm Springs, Calif. The low
for the day was 43 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the Rockies and the Plateau region across the southern Plains
and the lower Mississippi Valley to the south Atlantic Coast.
   Thunderstorms will range from Florida and southern Alabama
across southern Georgia to southern South Carolina. Widely
scattered showers will fall over portions of eastern New York and
New England.
   Highs in the 80s or 90s were forecast over most of the nation;
in the 60s and 70s from the Great Lakes region to the northern and
mid-Atlantic coastal states; also in the 60s and 70s along the
Pacific Coast and in much of Washington state; around 100 degrees
over western portions of the Dakotas and between 100 and 110
degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
