<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Tatars 1stLd-Writethru   06-26 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Tatars, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0769,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tatar Protest Brutally Dispersed By Police</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with protester's report from
Tashkent. Picks up 3rd graf previous, ``The demonstration ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-wielding police brutally dispersed thousands
of Crimean Tatars who massed Sunday to protest the Kremlin's
refusal to give them back their homeland, a protester said Sunday.
   Server Tuvarchy, who took part in the demonstration in the
Uzbekistan capital of Tashkent, said 5,000 people gathered on the
city's Revolution Square in front of Communist party headquarters.
   ``The militia beat people,'' Tuvarchy, a Crimean Tatar activist,
said in a telephone interview. ``I myself took a girl to the
hospital who had been beaten so badly she was unconscious.''
   Tuvarchy said at least two people had been arrested. He said at
Tashkent's southern railway station, up to 300 Tatars had been held
by police to prevent them from taking part in the protest.
   In Moscow, dissident Valery Senderov quoted telephone reports
from Tashkent as saying up to 20,000 people took part in the
demonstration in front of Communist Party headquarters.
   ``The demonstration was roughly broken up by militiamen who
kicked the participants and beat them with clubs,'' Senderov said
in a telephone interview. He said reports telephoned from the scene
said hundreds may have been injured.
   The demonstration in Tashkent, about 1,600 miles southeast of
Moscow, was called to protest a government decision this month that
denied the Crimean Tatars their own homeland, Senderov said.
   On June 9, a government commission led by President Andrei A.
Gromyko ruled that there were ``no grounds for establishing a
Crimean autonomy.''
   That announcement was a major setback for the Tatars, who for
decades have been demanding a return to their ancestral homeland on
the Black Sea. Dictator Josef V. Stalin deported the Tatars from
the Crimea during World War II for allegedly collaborating with the
Nazis.
   The Crimean Tatars, who today number from 250,000 to 300,000,
were absolved of the war collaboration charge in 1967 but were
still not allowed to return en masse to the Crimea.
   A statement issued by the government commission said the Soviet
Union had eased restrictions that barred some Tatars from returning
to the Crimea.
   ``Since the middle of 1987, some 2,500 Crimean Tatars have been
granted residence permits and fixed up with jobs in the Crimea,''
the commission said.
   Crimean Tatar leaders have said those measures are inadequate,
and they have demanded the revival of the Crimean Tatar autonomous
region abolished by Stalin.
   Senderov said the demonstrators in Tashkent were also protesting
the treatment of Crimean Tatars in Moscow. Authorities in the
Soviet capital, bent on preventing Tatar demonstrations during the
nationwide Communist Party conference that begins Tuesday, are
immediately sending Crimean Tatars who arrive in Moscow back home,
Senderov said.
   One activist drew a 10-day jail term for arguing with a Moscow
police officer, he said.
   Senderov said the protesters in Tashkent managed to deliver a
petition listing their grievances to someone at Uzbekistan's
Communist Party headquarters before the protest was broken up.
   The government commission on the Crimean Tatars was established
last summer, after members of the ethnic group held an
extraordinary overnight demonstration at Red Square to press their
demands.
</TEXT>
