<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RailVote     06-26 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Vote,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Vote, Authority Must Seek New Solution To Transportation
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA BARNETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that helped defeat a referendum to finance
a rail and subway system in Dallas and its suburbs recommended
Sunday that a streamlined transit authority find other ways to ease
traffic congestion.
   Some 59 percent of the voters in Dallas and 15 suburbs, the area
served by Dallas Area Rapid Transit, rejected a proposal Saturday
to sell $1 billion in bonds to begin construction of a 93-mile
commuter rail system.
   The outcome was a victory for a group called Sensible Metro Area
Rapid Transit, which waged a small-budget campaign against the bond
proposal.
   ``I think DART is at a crossroads,'' former Dallas County Judge
David Fox, a leader of the citizens' group, said Sunday. ``The
election is now behind us. We now have the opportunity to reassess
where we are, what we've learned, and decide how to proceed from
here.''
   Saturday's results represented a turnabout from 1982, when 58
percent of the voters approved the measure that established DART, a
regional agency that was to develop a mass transit plan, including
a regional rail system.
   The decision throws the transit agency's future into question
because suburbs may call an election to withdraw from the agency.
Dallas suburbs contribute about 45 percent of its financing.
   The agency had no official contingency plan in the event of a
defeat and ``will return to the drawing board,'' said Charles
Anderson, its executive director.
   Some transit authority board members see the bond vote as a
mandate to develop a new transportation plan.
   Virtually all of Dallas' major freeways are at least 20 years
old, and most are burdened with traffic that meets or exceeds
capacity.
   Members of citizens' group say the area's traffic problems can
be solved by systems other than rail. Many of the recommendations
the group made Sunday included restructuring and streamlining the
transit authority, which critics say has become a bloated
bureaucracy.
   The group also recommended that the transit agency develop a
regional mobility plan that does not require incurring long-term
debt.
   Bill Ceverha, president of the citizens' group, said such a plan
could include some rail, but added, ``The election shows that the
economics of mass transit are so fundamentally different today than
they were a generation ago that they (the voters) regard fixed rail
and subway solutions as folly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
