<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru   06-26 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0796,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Condemns Nazi Euthanasia Programs As `Barbarism'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 8th graf, In his ... to UPDATE with
service in Lutheran church. Picks up 9th graf pvs, In a ... SUBS
last graf to UPDATE with pontiff retiring for night. Minor editing
to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALZBURG, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday condemned
the Nazi killings of thousands of severely handicapped people as
``the worst forms of barbarism'' and warned of mankind's potential
for violence and destruction.
   ``Human life should not be divided into that which is worth
living and that which is not,'' John Paul told 1,000 elderly, sick
and handicapped people in Salzburg's cathedral.
   In the German Third Reich, the Nazis killed thousands of the
handicapped under what they called ``euthanasia programs'' or mercy
killings.
   ``Decades ago, this division led to the worst forms of
barbarism,'' said the pontiff on the fourth day of his five-day
visit to Austria.
   The 50th anniversary of Austria's annexation by Nazi Germany has
prompted widespread soul-searching in this Alpine nation. Jewish
leaders have called on him to urge Austrians to come to terms with
the country's Nazi-era past.
   The pontiff often has called for greater respect for the
handicapped and for elderly people who are sick. The Vatican is
vehemently opposed to mercy killing, saying it goes against
Christ's teachings.
   After the prayer service, the pontiff donned a green robe and
warned of drug abuse in an outdoor Mass before 25,000 people in
Salzburg's Residence Square.
   In his homily, John Paul cited ``the fear of man's dangerous
potential for violence and destruction'' and urged parents to
``help your adolescent sons and daughters to withstand the
temptations of escaping into the sham world of drugs.''
   Also Sunday, in a gesture of reconciliation, the pontiff took
part in an ecumenical prayer service in a Lutheran church with
representatives of 12 other Christian churches and denominations in
Austria.
   Papal trip organizers said the service was one of the first in
which the pontiff has participated in a Protestant church.
   The pope said many Catholics and Protestants shared suffering in
World War II and ``experienced their deep union in Christ's cross,
especially in the extremely difficult ordeal of the concentration
camps,'' he said.
   In an afternoon talk to about 150 young people in Salzburg's
Catholic youth center, the pontiff again referred to the 1933-1945
Nazi era.
   ``Nobody can undo what has already been done,'' the pope said.
``Even the best psychologists cannot free us from the burden of our
past. Only the omnipotence of God can do this.''
   Many Austrians actively supported Adolf Hitler after the 1938
annexation, although the Nazis targeted Jews, leftist politicians
and other foes for immediate arrest and persecution.
   The pontiff told the youths that God ``cleanses even the
contaminated soil of our souls with the mercy of forgiveness and
thus gives us the strength for honest reconciliation with the
people we have hurt.''
   He also told them that if past failures are simply swept under
the rug, ``they will poison our spiritual environment.''
   On Saturday, he called the suffering of Jewish and Christian
victims of the Nazis ``a gift to the world.''
   Four American Jews said Sunday that they were beaten by Austrian
police when they demonstrated against the pope's meetings with
Austrian President Kurt Waldheim.
   The four made the charge during a news conference at Israel's
Ben Gurion Airport and also said they encountered anti-Semitism
from Austrian people.
   Rabbi Avi Weiss of the Riverdale Synagogue in New York said he
and three students were beaten by police after they displayed a
large photograph of Waldheim in a Nazi uniform at Mauthausen, a
former concentration camp that the pope visited.
   Waldheim has denied allegations by Jewish groups that he
participated in war crimes while serving with the German army in
the Balkans during World War II.
   In Vienna, the Kurier daily newspaper reported that Austrian
television canceled an evening broadcast of the film version of a
story the pontiff wrote in 1960 when he was bishop of Krakow,
Poland.
   The newspaper said that RAI Italian radio and television
requested the cancellation so that the new film can first be shown
to the pope at a private screening in July.
   Austrian television will show the film version of the pope's
work, called ``The Goldsmith's Shop,'' this fall, Kurier said.
   The pontiff retired for the night in Salzburg. He was scheduled
to return to Rome from Innsbruck Monday evening.
</TEXT>
