<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Government     06-26 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Government,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Plans Reform of Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II plans to announce an overhaul of
the Vatican government aimed at streamlining the organization,
Italian newspapers reported Sunday.
   The reorganization is to be announced Tuesday, the day the
pontiff is scheduled to formally install 25 cardinals.
   The reforms will increase the Roman Catholic Church's control
over the Vatican bank, give the Secretariat of State more power and
establish a commission for relations between the Vatican and its
lay employees, the newspapers said.
   The church hierarchy has been discussing the reform of the
Vatican government, known as the Curia, for several years.
   The Milan-based newspaper Corriere della Sera reported the plan
would give the College of Cardinals responsibility for supervising
the Vatican bank, officially called the Institute for Religious
Works, which has traditionally answered only to the pope.
   The bank has been the subject of controversy since Italian
authorities issued arrest warrants in February 1987 for its
president, American Archbishop Paul Marcinkus, and two of its lay
employees in connection with Italy's largest banking scandal.
   Prosecutors accused the men of being accessories to the
fraudulent bankruptcy of the Banco Ambrosiano in 1982.
   Italy's Constitutional Court ruled earlier in July that Italian
courts could not prosecute the three because the Vatican was
considered a sovereign state under treaties between Italy and the
Vatican.
   According to the newspaper reports, the reform will trim the
influence of the Vatican's ``Foreign Ministry'' _ the Council for
the Public Affairs of the Church _ making it just another
department of the Secretariat of State.
   The Council has functioned as part of the Secretariat but has
enjoyed a high profile and a certain amount of autonomy.
   The last major reform of the Curia was announced in 1967 by Pope
Paul VI. It provided that modern languages could be used in
official documents, made diocesan bishops members of all Vatican
government departments and implemented changes brought about by the
Second Vatican Council, which ran from 1962-65.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
