<HEAD>Cuba Blames South Africa For Increased Cuban Presence in Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with South African foreign
minister's comments. Picks up 11th graf pvs, ``Valdes would ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Cuban official on Sunday admitted
an increased Cuban military presence in southern Angola but
defended the move as an appropriate response to what he called a
brutal South African attack on the area.
   But Foreign Minister R.F. Botha said Sunday he has warned the
Cubans that the military buildup could start an explosive
confrontation.
   Jorge Risquet Valdes, chairman of the Cuban Communist Party's
foreign affairs committee, spoke at a news conference a day after
two days of U.S.-mediated peace talks on southern Africa ended in
Cairo.
   The United States, South Africa, Cuba and Angola participated in
the talks, the third in a series. The talks were aimed at resolving
the civil war in Angola, where Cuba has thousands of troops, and
ending South African rule in South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   A senior U.S. State Department official told reporters Sunday
the talks had achieved progress ``in atmosphere and procedure.''
But he said political decisions were necessary to bridge gaps
between the countries involved.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some
parties to the talks had hinted at concessions. He did not
elaborate.
   He said among new elements in the peace talks were Cuban-Angolan
agreement for total Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola and
Soviet-American contacts to resolve a number of international
problems, including southern Africa.
   ``Basic political decisions still have to be made, and there is
not much time to make them because of the military situation,'' the
official said.
   Valdes blamed an alleged South African attack on Angola last
December with 9,000 troops and heavy equipment for Cuba's military
buildup in the country.
   ``This brutal escalation launched by South Africa was really
what made it necessary for the Angolan government to ask Cuba for
an increase in forces in necessary quantity, both men and
equipment, in order to rebut this offensive and to overcome it,''
Valdes said.
   ``The increase of Cuban troops, we did not deny ... It is the
proportionate and appropriate response to an increase in brutal
attacks launched by South Africa on Angola.''
   Interviewed by the British Broadcasting Corp. on his way back to
Johannesburg, Botha said he told the Cubans that ``with the
closeness of a large number of military forces'' to the Namibian
border ``you only need a spark to set a big fire to explode.''
   Valdes would not discuss how many Cuban troops are in Angola. He
refused to confirm or deny South African claims that 15,000 to
17,000 Cubans now are in southern Angola and more than 50,000 in
the country as a whole.
   He said Cuba sent forces to Angola in 1975 at the request of
Luanda's Marxist government.
   In the peace talks, which started last month in London, the
United States has been trying to set up a formula using a Cuban
withdrawal from Angola as a trigger to get South Africa to start
granting Namibia independence.
   Valdes said final agreement would foreshadow a ``gradual and
total'' withdrawal of Cuba's military contingent.
   He gave no details. The leading Egyptian newspaper Al-Ahram said
the Angolan-Cuban delegation had offered a Cuban withdrawal program
to be complete in four years. South Africa said it should take no
more than eight months.
   A new round of talks is scheduled for next month in Cairo.
</TEXT>
