<HEAD>Japanese Foreign Minister Makes First Visit to Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6 grafs for grafs 3-6 pvs, ``We really ...'' to UPDATE
with Uno urging solution to Middle East problems, Japanese Red Army
condemnation. Pickup 7th pvs, `I am ... </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno toured a
West Bank refugee camp Sunday and met with Palestinian leaders who
urged him to press the United States to hold talks with the PLO.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres welcomed Uno at Ben Gurion
Airport. The 22-hour trip was the first visit to Israel by a
Japanese Cabinet minister. Uno, 65, also has visited Egypt, Jordan
and Syria on his Middle East tour.
   At a dinner hosted by Peres, Uno stressed the urgency of
reaching a Middle East peace settlement.
   ``The state of affairs in the West Bank and Gaza Strip is daily
shown on the televisions in Japan, and the Japanese people are
following the developments in this region with ... deep
apprehension,'' he said. ``The situation demands an early
solution.''
   Japan supports an independent Palestinian state and has urged
Israel to withdraw all its forces from the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East War.
It has also urged Israeli negotiations with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which Israel considers a terrorist group.
   In Beirut, Lebanon, the Japanese Red Army terrorist group
released a statement condemning Uno's visit to Israel. The group
launched a bloody attack on Lod airport near Tel Aviv in 1972 that
left 28 people dead.
   After his arrival, Uno visited the West Bank's Dheisheh refugee
camp, where he pledged $250,000 in Japanese aid to build a new
community center.
   ``I am fully aware of your indefatigable way of life under the
difficult conditions in the refugee camp and of the severe
situation in the West Bank and Gaza since last December,'' he told
a small group of Dheisheh residents.
   Japan will grant another $250,000 to U.N. relief operations in
the territories, he said.
   After briefly stopping at the Western Wall, the holiest site for
Jews in Jerusalem's old city, Uno held a 50-minute meeting with six
Palestinian leaders at an east Jerusalem hotel.
   Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij, Palestinian leader Faisal Husseini,
Gaza lawyer Faez Abu Rahme, journalist Radwan Abu Ayyash, former
mayor Mustafa Natsche and businessman Said Kenaan attended the
meeting.
   The meeting was held behind closed doors, but the Palestinians
issued a statement saying they welcomed Japan's support for an
international Mideast peace conference as well as its call for
Israel to withdraw from the occupied territories.
   Kenaan told reporters the Arab leaders urged Uno to pressure the
United States to respond to a document released by PLO leader
Yasser Arafat's senior political adviser, Bassan Abu-Sherif.
   The document, publicized this month, proposed negotiations with
Israel toward a two-state solution.
   ``We asked him to press the U.S. to accept the Abu-Sherif
document,'' Kenaan said. ``We endorse _ every one of us _ the
Abu-Sherif statement and hope it will convince the Israelis that
Palestinians are ready for peace.''
   During an afternoon meeting with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
Uno shared his impressions of the difficult living conditions he
saw at the refugee camp.
   Shamir responded by urging Japan to participate in his proposal
to revamp the camps and find new housing for the residents, said
Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner.
</TEXT>
