<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FiskeHome     06-26 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fiske Home,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jamie Fiske's Parents Open Home For Transplant Families</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who camped in a hospital lounge
while their ailing daughter awaited a liver transplant opened a
house Sunday to help other families avoid that same ordeal.
   Charles and Marilyn Fiske held an open house Sunday at The
Family Inn, a renovated structure here with room for 10 families.
The families can stay at the house, located near area hospitals,
for $10 per night.
   ``The child who is ill is pretty well taken care of,'' Fiske
said as dozens of neighbors, builders and sponsors of the project
toured the rambling home. ``It's the rest of the family that can't
understand why it's going on. It's just overwhelming. If they can
come some place, put their feet up and have their families come on
weekends, it doesn't make it go away but it just puts it in
perspective.''
   The house has a large kitchen, extra bathrooms, several pay
phones, a laundry in the basement and a den with a television.
   ``I think there's two things we're providing,'' said Fiske.
``One of them is a place to stay. Another is contact with other
families.''
   Marilyn Fiske had her hands full Sunday making sure daughter
Jamie didn't make a clean sweep of a cookie tray set out for
visitors. Now 6, Jamie was running, jumping and playing along with
other youngsters at the open house.
   In the fall of 1982 a family in Alpine, Utah, saw a television
report of a speech made by Charles Fiske at a New York
pediatrician's convention pleading for help. Four days later, the
Utah family lost their 11-month-old son in an accident. The boy's
liver was transplanted into Jamie in an operation Nov. 5, 1982, in
Minneapolis.
   The hospital where the operation took place was, at the time,
one of the few in the country that performed the operation. The
Fiskes, from Bridgewater, Mass., spent three months in Minnesota.
The couple spent the first week living in the hospital waiting
room. Subsequently, Mrs. Fiske found a boarding house and her
husband visited from Massachusetts on weekends.
   Mrs. Fiske began taking notes of some of the problems she and
the family encountered during Jamie's hospital stay. She said the
notes were the beginning of The Family Inn.
</TEXT>
