<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought-diminished Mississippi River near St. Louis
re-opened to more than 500 barges after a three-day dredging
operation, while Texas farmers whose cattle had to eat cactus were
faced with flash floods after weekend thunderstorms dumped five to
10 inches of rain.
   The weather cooled dramatically around the southern Great Lakes
but remained hot and humid in the South.
   Meanwhile, in Washington, the chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee estimated Sunday that food prices will increase 2 percent
to 4 percent next year because of the drought.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., interviewed on CBS' ``Face the
Nation,'' also said his committee would monitor market activity in
farm products.
   Thirty-nine tows pushing the barges on the Mississippi had been
idled by the low water levels but were able to move through the
newly dug channel by Saturday midnight, Coast Guard Cmdr. Tim
Josiah said Sunday.
   An additional 1,000 barges were reported waiting at St. Louis to
head down river.
   At Memphis, Tenn., on the lower Mississippi, Brig. Gen. Thomas
A. Sands of the Army Corps of Engineers said Sunday the river may
fall soon to less than 20 percent of its normal flow.
   However, both Sands, who is president of the Mississippi River
Commission, and Rear Adm. William Leahy of the Coast Guard
predicted that commercial traffic on the lower Mississippi will
continue through the summer although periodic barge backups and
groundings can be expected.
   Sands and William Leahy toured the area with Robert Page,
assistant secretary of the Army for civil works.
   ``There are problems on the river, but they are manageable,''
Page said. ``We'll keep it open.''
   In Nebraska, the high temperature failed to clear the 100-degree
mark for the first time in eight days Sunday, but drought
conditions lingered and people talked more and more about the
resemblance to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
   Monsigner Edward O'Donnell of Omaha recalled residents flocking
to the air-conditioned Orpheum Theater to avert the heat in the
1930s. He said the summers of 1934 and 1936 were ``scorchers.''
   ``I remember we slept on the porch at night to keep cool,''
O'Donnell said.
   Gretchen Musser, 79, of Omaha, was living in rural Rising City
in 1934, when only 14 inches of rain fell in Nebraska. It was the
lowest annual rainfall since 1864.
   ``It was hot for weeks at a time. Real hot. Without letting up.
It lasted year after year,'' she said.
   Severe thunderstorms slashed across Alabama Sunday and caused
serious damage in the southeast corner of the state, where two
homes were destroyed by what witnesses described as a tornado.
Dozens of vehicles were damaged when winds ripped part of the roof
off the Dothan airport.
   Emergency management officials reported no serious injuries from
the storm, which provided the second straight day of much-needed
rain for some drought-stricken areas.
   ``The rains (in Texas) ... have helped quite a bit,''
particularly in the southeast part of the state, said metereologist
Larry Peabody of the National Weather Service forecast center in
San Antonio, Texas.
   The weather service issued flash flood warnings for Real and
Uvalde counties near San Antonio, where three to five inches of
rain fell Saturday.
   In Arkansas, some rain showers fell across the southern
two-thirds of the state Saturday, but Lee Harrison, a deputy
meteorologist with the National Weather Service, said Sunday the
showers didn't amount to much.
   Although a day of prayer proclaimed for Sunday by Gov. Bill
Clinton didn't produce substantial rain, it did seem to have some
effect: ``Attendance is picking up,'' said the Rev. Harmon
Whitehurst of the United Methodist Church at Weiner.
</TEXT>
