<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Pride Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0871,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Thousands Attend Gay Marches</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf to show Hartford march occurred Saturday.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY20, FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay couples marched in matching colors, San Francisco's mayor
brought his family, and balloons were released to memorialize AIDS
deaths as half a million people participated in gay pride
celebrations nationally Sunday.
   Police estimated 100,000 people marched down New York's Fifth
Avenue, stopping for a period of silence as 10,000 balloons bearing
messages and poems to people who have died of AIDS were released.
Similar balloon releases occurred in San Francisco and West
Hollywood, Calif.
   ``The balloons are symbolic of the freedom we, as homosexuals,
have to fly free and be proud of what we are,'' said Kenn Kidd, an
organizer.
   About 25 members of three organziations _ Jews for Morality, the
National Coalition to Prevent the Spread of AIDS and the Committee
for the Defense of St. Patrick's _ protested opposite St. Patrick's
Cathedral, condemning homosexuals and shouting ``AIDS spreaders''
at parade participants.
   In Hartford, Conn., about 600 gay activists chanting ``Gay
bashing, we say no, homophobia's got to go,'' marched Saturday
through downtown to the state Capitol. Activists attributed a
bludgeoning death last month to anti-homosexual bias.
   Chicago's parade attracted several hundred marchers and many
more spectators, and ended with a rally that attracted about
70,000, police said.
   A focus was support of a proposed human rights ordinance
approved by a City Council committee Thursday that would prohibit
discrimination on the basis of age, martial status, disability or
sexual orientation. Church groups have lobbied against it.
   Chicago Mayor Eugene Sawyer was scheduled to speak at the rally
but didn't show up.
   In Seattle, three congressional candidates turned out to court
about 15,000 people who marched and rallied to cap a Lesbian and
Gay Pride Week.
   In San Francisco, Art Agnos became the first mayor to take part
in the city's annual Gay Freedom Day parade, which drew more than
160,000 marchers and spectators.
   Agnos rode with his family in a black 1931 Lincoln Continental.
The parade also featured 175 floats and contingents, escorted by
the group Dykes on Bikes, hundreds of leather-clad,
motorcycle-revving lesbians.
   In addition to the traditional sprinkling of female
impersonators and leather-clad, buttock-flashing cowboys, there
were more serious contingents, such as Living Sober, a group of
recovering drug addicts and alcoholics.
   In West Hollywood, gay couples wearing matching colors strolled
arm-in-arm along the parade route. Drill teams and marching bands
entertained 150,000 people in the 19th annual Los Angeles Gay and
Lesbian Pride Celebration.
   The parade grew somber as participants released 12,000 purple
helium-filled balloons, each bearing the name of a person with AIDS.
   ``The AIDS crisis has brought together the gay and lesbian
communities and has helped bring people out, not just to the
festival, but to their families and their friends,'' said organizer
Gary Jonker.
   ``I watched in 1982 and I don't know if there was any AIDS
groups present, said Gary Farnsworth, a student at City College of
San Francisco, watching the parade there. ``Then last year it
seemed so heavy into AIDS, which is valid _ it's important.
   ``For all the thousands of people marching today in this parade,
more than a thousand of them won't be here next year,'' he said.
   The AIDS-related concerns stem from the fatal virus' rampant
spread through the male homosexual community. Nationally, 65,099
AIDS cases have been reported since June 1981, resulting in 36,874
deaths.
</TEXT>
