<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PublicHousing-Vacancies     06-26 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Public Housing-Vacancies,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One In Six Of Chicago's Public Housing Units Sit Vacant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly one out of every six public housing units
in Chicago sits vacant while tens of thousands of applicants wait
for a place to live, a new study shows.
   Housing Authority executive director Vincent Lane attributed the
problem in part to street gangs who have taken over some of the
buildings, frightening residents away.
   ``Decent people know when these guys are in a building. They try
to get out. They move. When units become available in that
building, nobody takes them,'' Lane said.
   In the past year, 1,550 of the Chicago Housing Authority's
40,840 units, or more than four apartments a day, have become
uninhabitable, the Chicago Tribune reported in Sunday editions.
   A total of 6,218 units are vacant, according to the Chicago
Sun-Times.
   At the Robert Taylor Homes on the South Side, the Housing
Authority's largest public housing project, gangs have ``taken over
or have a foothold'' in half of the 56 buildings, Lane said.
   The vacancy rate has risen to 40 percent in some of the
buildings controlled by gangs, compared with 6 percent at two
Robert Taylor buildings not dominated by gangs, he said.
   ``The problem is critical. The more vacancies you have, the more
they proliferate. It's like a cancer eating away,'' said Lane.
   Cuts in funds, labor and equipment are also to blame for the
problem, Lane and other officials said.
   But others blamed bureaucratic inefficiency. Former Housing
Authority board member Patricia Crowley contended that many of the
40,000 people on the waiting lists are dead or can't be located.
   The authority has cut its work force from 2,880 to 1,957 in the
last year because of federal cutbacks, the Tribune said.
   So, instead of quickly repairing apartments when tenants move
out, the authority boards up units, which are often run-down after
years of abuse by tenants.
   But by boarding up the apartments, the authority is telling
gangs ``that they can move in and do their number on it,'' Lane
said.
</TEXT>
