<HEAD>Famous Divorce Lawyer Blasts Televised Rape Accusation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 11-12 `The lawyer' to restore full name of Ms.
Barrett-Whitney.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divorce lawyer Marvin Mitchelson on Sunday
described two former clients who claimed he raped them as
``professional extortionists'' after they described the alleged
attacks on a television program.
   ``It's ridiculous because I've spent my life defending women,
not attacking them. After their complaints were filed, I went and
took a lie detector test on both women, and it came out 100 percent
that I had had nothing to do with them,'' Mitchelson said.
   He commented after the CBS program ``60 Minutes'' featured an
investigation that began after Kristen Barrett-Whitney and Patricia
French made the allegations against the lawyer.
   ``These women are charlatans, they can cry on cue,'' he said.
``They know it didn't happen, and I know it didn't happen. They're
professional extortionists, that's what you run into in this
business. When you're a high-profile figure, these people come
after you.''
   Ms. Barrett-Whitney said she paid Mitchelson $25,500 to
represent her in a palimony action, only to have him rape her in a
bathroom. The CBS program quoted Ms. French as saying she was raped
by Mitchelson and another former client as saying he fondled her
and took a bubble bath in front of her.
   Ms. Barrett-Whitney and Ms. French complained to police, who
recorded a conversation between Mitchelson and Ms. Barrett-Whitney
in which the attorney said, ``I have no bad feelings against you,
and I wasn't in any way trying to traumatize you,'' the CBS report
said.
   Los Angeles Assistant District Attorney Dan Murphy said: ``There
certainly are things that Mr. Mitchelson says in that tape which
make the hair in the back of my neck stand up. I say, you know
something, something's cooking here.''
   But the district attorney's office decided there was not enough
evidence to prosecute, Murphy said.
   The ``60 Minutes'' report said that when Mitchelson was told
about the story, ``he cried and pleaded with us not to air this
report,'' offering ``10 great stories'' if the program dropped the
Mitchelson piece.
   ``I urged them not to do it because it was untrue, but it's a
misrepresentation for (60 Minutes correspondent) Mike Wallace to
say I begged him not to do it,'' Mitchelson said from his Los
Angeles office.
   The lawyer said Ms. Barrett-Whitney has 13 aliases and has filed
seven different lawsuits totalling $300 million against several
professionals, doctors, psychiatrists, lawyers, dentists, ``all
claiming the same thing.''
   He said Ms. Barrett-Whitney came to him for palimony and later
several other suits, but he refused to take the other lawsuits.
   ``When I refused to take them, then she decided to leave me and
claim that I sexually attacked her,'' Mitchelson said.
   He said Ms. French wanted him to sue a minister for a supposed
sexual attack.
   ``When I found it to be groundless, I said I wouldn't do it.
Even still, she sent me nice letters for months trying to get me to
take the case, months after the fictitious attack on her supposedly
happened,'' he said.
</TEXT>
