<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0874,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montana-S.D. Fire Out of Control Again; Blazes Elsewhere Contained</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with fire again getting out of
control along Montana-South Dakota border, Idaho firefighters
controlling Tyndall Meadows blaze. Picks up 5th graf, `In Old ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A week-old fire along the Montana-South Dakota border broke away
from an army of more than 1,200 firefighters again Sunday and raced
northward six or seven miles across thousands of acres of timber,
officials reported.
   Officials were uncertain how many additional acres had burned,
but their best estimate was that the fire covered more than 50,000
acres Sunday night in the Custer National Forest, said Jack
Hendley, a spokesman at the Interagency Fire Center in Billings,
Mont.
   Meantime, the number of widespread forest and brush fires
continued to run far above average and to concern fire officials
across the nation, though some fires were being brought under
control.
   More than 700 acres of drought-seared grassland burned in
Southern California. At least 10 people were injured _ one
seriously enough to be hospitalized _ and four residences burned
before firefighters controlled a 215-acre blaze Saturday in the
high desert community of Apple Valley.
   Aided by overnight rainfall and cooler, humid weather, 200 Idaho
firefighters controlled the 137-acre Tyndall Meadows fire in the
Boise National Forest Sunday and planned to begin demobilizing
Monday.
   In Old Town, Maine, weekend rain also helped to remove the
immediate threat of forest fires in some areas, but rangers said
Sunday that rainfall was too light to make any difference in most
of the state's northern woods.
   A fire that scorched at least 200 acres in the Allagash region
of Maine was reported under control Sunday, but rangers said
lightning posed a constant danger.
   In the western Maine woods, Assistant Regional Ranger Kenny Wing
said Saturday's rain removed the danger for a couple of days.
   ``But with a little bit of sunshine and a little bit of wind,
we'll be right back where we were,'' Wing said.
   Flames from the Montana fire came within 300 yards of a ranch
near the South Dakota border Saturday night before firefighters and
air-dropped flame retardant turned the blaze away, officials said.
   ``It was very extreme, a pretty tense situation,'' said fire
information officer Michelle Ravnikar.
   Fire had burned 39,680 acres as of Sunday morning. So far,
firefighting costs have topped $900,000 and are expected to reach
$1.75 million, and timber losses are predicted at $2.5 million.
   The Maine Forest Service reported 10 to 15 new fires a day last
week, compared with the usual two or three a day in June. As of
late last week, 556 fires had burned more than 2,200 acres this
year in Maine.
   Louisiana Office of Forestry firefighters normally battle about
100 fires during June, but so far this month 511 fires have been
reported.
   Approximately eight times as many acres of land have been lost
this month as in June 1987.
   High temperatures, consistently low humidity and windy days have
combined to make conditions excellent for fires and only a long,
steady rain will make things better, officials said.
</TEXT>
