<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WallStreet-Profits     06-26 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street-Profits,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: First Quarter Industry Profit Concentrated In 10
Investment Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten big investment banks accounted for 43
percent of the securities industry's first quarter profit,
indicating the impact of the October market crash still is being
felt by most U.S. firms, an industry trade group has reported.
   The industry posted a pre-tax profit of $1.1 billion in the
first quarter, compared with a $2.1 billion loss in fourth quarter
1987 and a $2 billion pre-tax profit for all of last year, the
Securities Industry Association said in a survey released Monday.
   Big investment banks constituting 2.5 percent of the New York
Stock Exchange member firms accounted for more than 43 of the
industry-wide profit, while just 23 percent of the NYSE firms
accounted for 61 percent of the profit, SIA stated.
   The figures indicated the ripples from the October crash still
were being felt mostly by the retail sector, where the bulk of the
nation's securities firms are focused, said SIA president, Edward
I. O'Brien.
   Industry-wide commission revenue fell by 25 percent, to $2.4
billion from $3.2 billion in the fourth quarter, for the worst
quarterly shjowing since fourth quarter 1985.
   Mutual fund revenue rose to $430 million in the first quarter
from $360 million in the previous three months, although it was
below the 1987 quarterly average of $552 million, SIA reported.
   At the same time, industry-wide trading profit surged 63 percent
higher, to $3.1 billion from $1.9 billion in fourth quarter 1987,
while investment profit fell to $828 million from $1.3 billion in
the fourth quarter, but remained far over the 1987 quarterly
average of $17 million.
   Revenue related to other activitites such as mergers and
acquisitions and private stock placements nearly equaled the $2.9
billion quarterly average for 1987, the report stated.
   Those results indicate firms concentrating in investment banking
and trading continued to do well, ``while the retail hemisphere has
almost ground to a halt,'' the SIA stated.
   The report was included in the group's ``Trends'' publication,
which is issued several times a year.
</TEXT>
