<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-88 2000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-BusinessMirror     06-26 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sense and Nonsense in the Stock Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs. John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New evidence has come in lately to buttress the
widely espoused belief that the stock market makes no sense.
   On May 17, the government reported a sharp drop in the trade
deficit and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 21.22
points.
   On June 14, the government reported another sharp drop in the
trade deficit and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
25.07 points.
   At least one large bank ran advertisements noting these
divergent performances, and suggested its certificates of deposit
as an alternative to stocks for people who wanted investments they
could understand.
   The bank had a point. Any investor with a strong desire for
order, simplicity and stability is probably better off avoiding any
strategy that depends on the day-to-day fluctuations of the stock
market.
   But to the charge that the market behaves irrationally, its
advocates respectfully plead innocent.
   Though the reasoning may get convoluted at times, they say,
there is almost always a method behind the madness portrayed on the
ticker tape.
   In the case of the recent trade reports, said Hugh Johnson, an
analyst at First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y., the explanation for
the market's differing responses lay not far below the surface.
   ``In both instances,'' he noted, ``the trade deficit declined
significantly.
   ``However, the decline in the March deficit (reported in May)
signaled that the economy may be strengthening, and the decline in
the April deficit (reported in June) signaled that the economy may
be weakening.
   ``The March trade deficit improved because exports surged,
suggesting that domestic demand in West Germany, Japan, etc., was
strengthening and was placing pressure on U.S. manufacturers to
meet that demand.
   ``This was viewed by the financial markets as inflationary.
   ``The April trade deficit improved because imports declined,
suggesting that domestic demand in the U.S. was slowing. This
suggested inflation may not be as big a problem as it has been made
out to be.
   ``The two events, when taken together and reviewed along with
the market's reaction to other recent releases, demonstrate how
important it is to the financial markets that the economy slows
down from the pace of the prior three quarters.''
   In other words, stock traders' reactions to the trade reports
were simply a new variation on a theme that has become familiar on
Wall Street in the 1980s: ``Good news is bad news,'' and vice versa.
   Favorable news for near-term business activity conjures up
images of increased inflation, rising interest rates and
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve, all of which could serve
as prelude to a recession.
   Unfavorable news for near-term business activity evokes visions
of reduced inflation, falling interest rates and stimulative credit
policy from the Fed, all of which could set the stage for renewed
growth later on.
   Suppose you have worked your way through all this and you still
don't buy it.
   How could one monthly report on a single aspect of the economy
send fears of inflation rippling through the market, and another
four weeks later persuade thousands of investors that things were
not so bad after all?
   Well, one could argue, expectations do not really change that
radically. When the market rises or falls 20 points as measured by
the Dow, it is actually moving up or down by about 1 percent to
adjust for the latest information received.
   And at the same time, one could acknowledge that this
``adjustment'' process is emotional, messy and sometimes outright
violent.
   Most devotees of the stock market will readily admit to all
that. Just don't try to tell them it is nonsensical.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
